<html><head><title>Americans for a Balanced Budget in the Press - AMERICANS FOR A BALANCED BUDGET</TITLE></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center>
<blockquote>
<img src="/abb/images/hdr-pr.gif">
<P>

<h3>Americans for a Balanced Budget in the Press
</H3></CENTER>
<BR><P>


<p>
May 9, 1996			
<P>
US News & World Report, May 6, 1996   Page 24
<P>
Labor Intensive
<P>
Republican leaders are preparing an all-out attack designed to counter a $35 million campaign mounted by labor unions to help elect Democratic candidates this fall. Among the legislative plans being considered: a proposal that would require more-detailed disclosure of political lobbying and contributions by union members and a bill that would make it easier for workers to resign from a union. In addition, GOP leaders are expected to tout a new poll of 1000 union members that purportedly shows a split between the AFL-CIO's official political policies and the view of its rank-and-file over such issues as welfare reform, the minimum wage and a $500-per-child tax credit. The sponsor of the survey, a conservative organization called Americans for a Balanced Budget, also claims that about 70 percent of union members would likely ask for part of their dues back if they were aware of the difference between their view and those of the union leaders.
<P>

The Wall Street Journal, Tuesday, April 30, 1996   Page 1
<P>
Union Politics spark mixed reaction, survey shows.
<P>
With the AFL-CIO vowing to spend at least $35 million to defeat House Republicans this fall, rank and file union members have been mostly mute. But silence doesn't mean support, says Americans for a Balanced Budget, a right-leaning lobby. In fact, the group says its own poll, to be released today, shows widespread dissent.
<P>
Republican pollster Frank Luntz questioned 1000 union members last week and found that 41% "strongly oppose" the AFL-CIO's spending plan while only 14% "strongly support" it. The remaining 45% have no strong opinion. Gerald McEntee, president of the American Federation of State, County, and Municipal Employees union and head of the AFL-CIO's political efforts, said the AFL-CIO's own surveys show overwhelming support.
<P>

The Washington Times, Wednesday, May 1, 1996 Page A18
<P>
What union members think
<P>
Perhaps more galling than the fact that the AFL-CIO has launcheda massive - and dubiously legal - political campaign to unseat freshmen House Republicans is the fact that they are wagin this campaign with the wages of their members, and without the workers' consent.
<P>
A poll conducted by Frank Luntz for Americans for a Balanced Budget, released yesterday, reveals just how far the union bosses have strayed from the priorities of the union rank and file. When union members were asked whether they supported or opposed the AFL-CIO's decision to spend $35 million in dues in an effort to defeat Republicans, 62 percent said they opposed the unions' political use of dues. Only 31 percent supported the big l;abor campaign.<P>
Union bosses like to pretend that they are "representing" workers in the political arena. But it's news to the workers. Less than half of the union members polled knew that the national labor unions were garnishing their wages to pay for a national political campaign. And only 19 percent knew that they were entitled to demand a refund on the portion of their dues apenst on politicking. Told about that right, a majority of the worker said they wanted those dollars back. As od now, the unions do not have an accounting to members for how their union dues are spent. Asked if they would support a new law to require full disclosure of where their due dollars are going, an overwhelming 84 percent of union members said yes.
<P>
The disconnect between big labor bosses and the workers becomes even more pronounced whenthe union members are asked - free of partisan labels - what they think of key proposals being advanced by the Republican Congress. Not suprisingly, workers were not too patient with those who don't work: Eightly-seven percent support welfare that requires work and I slimited of duration. They also support a balanced budget ammendment by a huge margin, with 82 percent in favor of a constitutional requirement that Washington keep its fiscal house in order. And more than three-fourths of the union workers voiced their support for tax cuts for working families.
<P>
Twice as many of the workers describe themselves as Democrats than Republicans. But the real leanings of the workers come through when asked if they are conservative, moderate or liberal: 44 percent call themselves conservative, 32 percent are moderates, and only 18 percent say liberal. Given that union bosses are lobbying for liberal policies, is it any surprise that well over half of the workers polled say that the attack on the Republican Congress is no way to spend their union dues?
<P>
What could better illustrate the Democrats' true concern for the "workers" whose interest they are always invoking? Presidentr Clinton and his compatriots are more than happy to benefit from money that has been taken from workers against their wishes. Reductions in employees take-home pay are all right, it seems, as long as the differenc ends up in Democratic campaign coffers.
<P>

</DOC>
