<html>
<head>
<title>General Purposes</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/bradley/bg.gif">
<blockquote><blockquote>
<center>
<img src="/bradley/hdr-lh.gif"><p>
<br>
<h3>Milwaukee's Bradley Legacy<br>
Continues as Foundation<br>
Moves to Historic "Lion House"<br>
</h3>
<img src="/bradley/lionhouse.gif">
</center>
<P>
In Milwaukee's sesquicentennial year, the Lynde and Harry Bradley Foundation has taken stewardship for one of the community's architectural treasures, relocating it headquarters to the landmark "Lion House" in the First Ward Triangle Historic District. Noted as the city's "finest surviving pre-Civil War home" and named for the carved lions crouched upon its portico, the Lion House represents the aspirations of Milwaukee's immigrant settlers and the community's heritage of civic participation.<P>

Built in 1855 as the vision of German immigrant Edward Diederichs, the Lion House has been the home of many prominent citizens, including entrepreneur Henry Mann in the 1860's banker and civic leader John Johnston in the 1890's, and, in the 1940's, president of Marine National Exchange Bank, Eliot Fitch, who was also an active leader in many local civic institutions. Architecturally restored and converted to commercial office space by James A. and James D. Hummert in the 1980's, the building was chosen last year by the Foundation's Board of Directors as a headquarters that will mark the continuing and active presence of the legacy of Lynde and Harry Bradley in the Milwaukee community.<P>

Combining the institution's office needs with a project of historical restoration is particularly apt at the time of Milwaukee's 150th anniversary, said Foundation President Michael S. Joyce, noting that "our Board is very intentionally sending the message that the Bradley Foundation is at once rooted in Milwaukee's heritage and looking to its future." The move, Joyce added, "ensures the preservation and stewardship of one of our city's most charming landmarks and provides efficient office space in a convenient location for the Foundation's philanthropic operations."<p>

The Lynde and Harry Bradley Foundation, established in 1985, is a private, independent grantmaking organization directed to supporting research and education. Due to its modest size and near-downtown location, the Lion House will be a suitable headquarters for the Milwaukee-based institution's small staff. Extensive renovations consistent with the building's architectural integrity were planned by Uihlein Architects and executed by D.G. Beyer, Inc. to coordinate operational and historic objective.
<br>
<P>

<center><a href="/bradley/bio.html"><img src="/bradley/tl-bf.gif"
 border="0"><a href ="/bradley/curint.html"><img src="/bradley/
tl-cpi.gif" border="0"></a><a href="/bradley/grants.html"><img
src="/bradley/tl-gmp.gif" border="0"></a><br>
