<a name="10">
<P>
<BR><H3>
Letters to the Editor</H3><BR>
<P>
 Thank you for the newsletter about
the Joyce Foundation. 
I know you write from a special viewpoint,
as is your right.  You'd have a better chance to sell
that view if you got the details right instead of getting into
a position where facts undermine your whole argument. Among the
serious errors in the article are these lesser ones pertaining
to me:
<P>
Daly is) &quot;a practicing Catholic.&quot;
That error made my Catholic mother-in-law happy but I remain a
non-practicing Protestant.
<P>
(Daly is) &quot;an active Democrat.&quot;
Nope,  just a registered, inactive Democrat who has crossed the
line often (and privately).
<P>
&quot;A lieutenant said...&quot; Nope.
Colonels makes those statements, lieutenants just get shot.
<P>
&quot;Daly did confess that he had
himself attended Columbia Journalism School on a $600 scholarship.&quot;
Wrong. I have never applied for or received a scholarship. At
Columbia I did get that money by winning a competition to determine
which student had acquired the best understanding of the laws
governing libel.
<P>
As your concluding lines suggested,
I have taken another look at the direction the Joyce Foundation
is heading. I am delighted with the course and hope I can help
Deborah Leff maintain it.
<P>
Charles U. Daly
Director, John F. Kennedy
Library Foundation
Boston, MA
<P>
<BR>
<BR><I>
Daly is the former president --and currently a trustee -- of the Joyce Foundation.
</I>
<P>
<br>
Congratulations on Alicia Shepard's meticulously researched and well written study
of Pew's foray into civic journalism [&quot;Buying Press Coverage:
How Pew's Civic Journalism Projects Put Newspapers, Radio and
Television Stations on the Payroll,&quot; vol. 1, no. 7].
<P>
While civic journalism may skew reporting
away from &quot;hard&quot; news and demanding examination of government
(and away form cynicism, its supporters would add), your article
displayed no such bias toward either side of the debate.
<P>
I was impressed and look forward to
future detailed examinations of foundations' activities.</FONT>
<P>
William Raney, Esq.
Copilevitz and Canter, P.C.
BillRa9342@aol.com
<P>
<BR>
I wanted to tell you how much I enjoy
<I>Foundation Watch</I>. It tells me an awful lot about some villains
I didn't know nearly enough about, including the wicked Rebecca
Rimel. It is sickening to see what has happened to the Pew Foundation
under her regime, although there must have been some rot there
to have seen hiring her as a good idea in the first place. As
someone old enough to have recalled Howard Pew while he was still
alive (he was a doughty warrior in the labor-management wars of
the 30s and 40s, among other things) I can only be saddened by
yet one more 180 degree turn in a foundation that was set up for
totally different purposes than those which it now brazenly carries out.
<P>
Francis A. O'Connell Jr.
Grass Valley, CA
<P>
P.S. Almost forgot <I>Culture Watch</I>.  Super!!
<P><I>
O'Connell is a retired lawyer and foundation executive.</I>
<P>
