<P>
<a name="intro"></a><h3> Introduction</h3>
<P>
 Concern for the natural environment is an American tradition
with a long and proud history.  The Americans who created modern
industrial society and populated its urban centers in the late
19th and early 20th centuries also established national conservation
organizations.  Because they wanted to retain and enjoy the resources
of nature and pass them on to later generations, they organized
the National Wildlife Federation,
the National Audubon Society and
the Izaak Walton League of America,
and worked with local conservation groups to protect habitat and
maintain the amenities of environmental beauty and recreation.
<P>
 In 1970, millions of Americans celebrated the first Earth
Day.  This event mobilized thousands of activists and spawned
a new generation of environmental groups: The Natural
Resources Defense Council, the Environmental
Defense Fund, Environmental Action,
and the Environmental Policy
Institute were among the new advocacy groups that joined the older
resource conservation and wilderness preservation organizations.
 These groups, however, wanted to impose on the United States
a new philosophy of environmental protection.  They believed the
federal government should exercise primary responsibility for
solving environmental problems, and they aggressively promoted
an agenda of national public policies.  Their ideas were rapidly
adopted by the old-line conservation groups.  A new and powerful
political force was born.
<P>
 The new environmental movement provoked a flurry of legislative
activity.  The National
Environmental Policy Act was signed into law on January 1, 1970.
 Congress then passed the Clean Air
Act (1970), the Clean Water Act
(1972), the Federal
Insecticide, Fungicide, and Rodenticide Act (1972), the Endangered
Species Act (1973), and the Resource
Conservation and Recovery Act (1976), among many others.  More
laws followed.  By the end of the 1980s, environmental bills accounted
for nearly one-fifth of bills presented to Congress
and almost one-quarter of those enacted into law.
<P>
 The Reagan Administration
has been portrayed as opposed to environmental legislation, but
President Reagan signed laws like
the 1984 amendments to the Resource
Conservation and Recovery Act, which gave the federal government
&quot;cradle-to-grave&quot; authority over waste management. 
The Reagan Administration also dramatically increased environmental
enforcement.  For instance, between 1983 and 1989 the Justice
Department more than tripled the amount of fines levied against
those found guilty of &quot;environmental crimes.&quot;
<P>
 George Bush rapidly accelerated
the process.  He pledged to be the &quot;environmental president&quot;
and introduced and signed into law the Clean
Air Act Amendments of 1990, which regulates actual and potential
sources of air pollution from factories and autos to lawnmowers
and grain silos.  It is the nation's most costly environmental
legislation.  His Administration presided over an explosion in
environmental rulemaking--<I>National
Journal</I> labelled Bush the &quot;regulatory president&quot;--as
well as substantial increases in environment-related spending
and federal land acquisition.<BR>

<P><a name="what"></a>
<B>WHAT PRICE ENVIRONMENTALISM?</B>
<P>
 The government's environmental activism has been costly.  The
Environmental Protection
Agency has estimated that Americans spend well over $150 billion
per year complying with environmental regulations--over two percent
of Gross Domestic Product (GDP).
 Local governments must comply with nearly 175 unfunded federal
mandates and have to test drinking water for over 100 separate
substances.  Under one hypothesis of risk and cost,
the Office of Management
and Budget has estimated that one waste disposal regulation--a
listing of certain wood-treating chemicals as hazardous wastes--imposes
costs of $5.7 <I>trillion</I> to avert one premature cancer death.
<P>
 When businesses try to absorb the costs of complying with complex
environmental rules and permits, they are likely to pass on the
cost to consumers by raising the price of their products.  And
when they are confronted by the uncertainties of statutory interpretation
and the regulatory enforcement of environmental law they may decide
to slow the development and application of new technologies.
<P>
 Environmental regulation is increasingly expensive and, many
argue, less effective in achieving its goals, particularly in
the area of risk reduction.  Dr. William Cooper,
an ecologist at Michigan State
University, observes: &quot;We're really just about at the end
of the reductions in risk that you can achieve by the conventional
approach, which is to crank down on the pollution coming out of
the end of the pipe.  Now we're into more subtle issues.  How
clean do we really want our environment?  How much are we really
willing to pay for it?&quot;
<P>
 Nor are the regulatory trade-offs only ones of cost against benefit.
 It is also increasingly clear that attempting to improve environmental
quality in one area can hurt the environment in other areas. 
For example, EPA regulations
require the incineration of certain dioxin-contaminated wastes.
 Yet an incinerator that cannot meet the EPA's destruction standard
for dioxin may produce two barrels of dioxin-contaminated ash
for every barrel of dioxin-contaminated waste that it burns. 
Under current federal law, this ash cannot be put in a landfill.
 <I>The </I><I>New York Times</I> revealed
that ash of this kind from an incinerator at an abandoned Arkansas
chemical factory had to be stored in perpetuity in a $300,000
facility built for that purpose.  The total cost of that single
&quot;cleanup&quot; operation was over $25 million and could reach
up to $175 million.
<P>
 Or consider the Endangered
Species Act (ESA).  Under the Act, landowners lose the right to
use their land as they see fit when an endangered animal is discovered
on it.  Landowners cannot build or enlarge their homes, plant
crops, or cut down trees.  Rather than protect wildlife, the ESA
punishes landowners, in effect, for creating or maintaining a
species habitat.  The Act creates disincentives for protecting
endangered species.  Michael Bean of the
Environmental Defense Fund (EDF)
observes that landowners who find an endangered species on their
property may well decide to destroy it and its habitat before
it is discovered by federal authorities--a process
some call &quot;shoot, shovel, and shut up.&quot;  Nonetheless,
EDF and most other environmental groups remain steadfast supporters
of the ESA.<BR>

<P><a name="media"></a>
<B>MEDIA SKEPTICISM</B>
<P>
 The late journalist Warren Brookes was
among the first writers to expose the economic ignorance of environmental
policymakers and challenge their misuse of science.  His example
has been followed by writers for <I>Forbes</I>,
<I>The </I><I>Washington Times</I> and
the <I>Detroit News</I>, among other publications.
 Conservative and libertarian publications like <I>Reason,
</I><I>Insight, </I><I>Human
Events</I>, and <I>National Review</I>
also have focused attention on the failings of conventional environmental
analysis.  More recently, the major media have begun to look skeptically
at the claims of environmentalism.
<P>
<ul>
 <li>In December 1990, the popular
CBS News program &quot;60
Minutes&quot; aired a story which concluded that acid rain posed
little environmental threat.  The program quoted scientists who
refused to justify the $4 to $7 billion cost of an acid rain control
program that Congress had passed earlier
in the year.
<P>
 <li>In March 1993, the <I>New
York Times</I> published &quot;What Price Cleanup?&quot; a five-part
series that asserted &quot;many scientists, economists and Government
officials have reached the dismaying conclusion that much of America's
environmental program has gone seriously awry&quot; because &quot;environmental
policy has too often evolved largely in reaction to popular panics,
not in response to sound scientific analyses of which environmental
hazards pose the greatest risks.&quot;  The series challenged
the Superfund program, the reliability of animal
tests to assess chemical risk, and the need for a ban on ocean
dumping, among other policies.
<P>
 <li> In November 1993, ABC
News' &quot;20/20&quot; documented how enforcement of the Endangered
Species Act devastated some Riverside County, California homeowners.
 To protect the endangered Stephens'
Kangaroo Rat, homeowners were forbidden to clear firebreaks around
their homes.  When fires swept through the county in 1993, 29
homes (and rat habitat) were lost.
<P>
 <li>In December 1993, <I>U.S.
News &amp; World Report</I> published an in-depth look at &quot;The
Doomsday Myths&quot;--fear of species extinction and overpopulation.
 The story's conclusion: &quot;Environmentalists' penchant for
doomsaying is coming back to haunt them.&quot;
<P>
 <li>In April 1994, a highly-rated
ABC
News special  &quot;Are We Scaring Ourselves to Death?&quot; showed
how the federal Superfund program actually <I>increased</I> the
risk to public health and safety.  An abandoned Colorado silver
mine called Smuggler Mountain was designated
a federal Superfund site in 1986.  Though there
was no evidence that local residents were in danger, the federal
cleanup plan called for the physical dislocation of 150 homes
so that four feet of dirt could be removed from the site.  Local
leaders opposed the EPA plan, and one doctor told ABC, &quot;If
you want to save lives in this valley, build us a new road.  Our
road is what kills people.&quot;
<P>
 <li>In September 1994, the <I>Los
Angeles Times</I> ran a three-part series, &quot;Living Scared:
Why Do the Media Make Life Seem So Risky?&quot; on the &quot;cry-wolf&quot;
stories that dominate media coverage of the environment.  The
series' headline declared &quot;We're safer and healthier than
ever--and also more afraid of what we eat, drink and breathe.
 Why the reality gap?  Too often, critics say, the media's coverage
fuels our fears.&quot;
<P>
</ul>
 These stories criticize failed government environmental policies
and the nonprofit lobbying organizations that helped put them
in place.  NRDC senior
attorney David Hawkins said as much on &quot;60
Minutes&quot;: &quot;The environmental community has spent almost
no effort attempting to even monitor the progress&quot; of government-sponsored
acid rain research.  Instead, &quot;we have been working on trying
to get legislation in Washington.&quot;
<P>
 Public dissatisfaction with &quot;regulate first, ask questions
later&quot; policies is growing.  In 1991, only 28 percent of
the American public thought environmental groups exaggerated threats
&quot;in order to get the public to pay attention to them.&quot;
 By 1994, the number was 42 percent.
<P>
 Yet although many policy experts and the public now recognize
the failings of much environmental policy, Washington's environmental
lobbies are unyielding.  &quot;We don't need a new paradigm&quot;
said David Doniger, a senior attorney at the Natural
Resources Defense Council who later joined the Clinton
White House.  Fifteen environmental groups that participated
in a joint fundraising appeal opposed any efforts to reform existing
environmental laws and called instead for their strengthening.
 Leaders of the groups typically have attributed public dissatisfaction
to bad publicity and poor public education, not inadequacies in
policy.  &quot;Our business is basically communications and we've
lost the imagination of the guy on the street,&quot; says Ted
Lee Eubanks of the National
Audubon Society.
<P>
 The <I>New York Times</I> series, &quot;What
Price Cleanup?&quot;, was particularly threatening to environmentalists.
 Keith Schneider, the lead author of the
series, was called a mouthpiece for polluting corporations in
a September 1993 article in <I>Sierra</I>, the magazine
of the Sierra Club.  An official
of the Hudson County Sierra
Club earlier published similar charges, as had former Greenpeace
analyst Peter Montague, founder and director
of the Environmental
Research Foundation.  One year later, the National
Wildlife Federation published &quot;The Truth About Dioxin&quot;
in the pages of <I>National Wildlife</I>.
 It too charged Schneider with inaccuracy, but provided little
substantive documentation.
<P>
 These stories side-stepped Schneider's main point--that environmental
regulations cost a lot and produce little.  Instead, they targeted
Schneider's sources--corporate executives or scientists who received
corporate research funding--and the alleged interest of corporations
like the <I>Times</I> in underplaying the risks of dioxin and
other chemicals.  Schneider replied in his own defense: &quot;By
trying to portray others as enemies, and by failing to understand
the cultural shifts in understanding in the U.S., the national
environmentalists have become an enemy of the very programs, policies
and laws they themselves espouse.&quot;<BR>
</SUP>
<P><a name="env"></a>
<B>ENVIRONMENTAL ISSUES IN THE POLLING BOOTH</B>
<P>
 The election returns of 1994 are one gauge of public attitudes.
 Polls show that voters support strong environmental protection,
but they also elect candidates who campaign for regulatory reform.
<P>
<ul>
 <li>The Endangered
Species Act was a central issue in the Texas Governor's race between
incumbent Ann Richards and challenger
George W. Bush, Jr.  Two Bush radio
ads attacked Richards for not working hard enough to protect property
owners' rights.  Attempting to save Richards from defeat, the <!--Clinton (Bill) Administration,-->Clinton
Administration announced that it would not restrict development
in central Texas to protect habitat for the golden-cheeked warbler.
<P>
 <li>In Pennsylvania, successful gubernatorial
candidate Tom Ridge campaigned against
costly federal air pollution control mandates on the state that
included more stringent new car emission standards and a requirement
that automakers sell electric cars.
<P>
 <li>In Oklahoma, Representative Mike
Synar was defeated in the Democratic primary
&quot;in part because of his steadfast support for tougher rules
on a range of environmental issues.&quot;  Other
environmental allies, including Representatives Dan Hamburg
(D-CA), Dan Glickman (D-KS), Karen Shepard
(D-UT), Tom Andrews (D-ME), Karan English
(D-AZ) and Senator Jim Sasser (D-TN) also
lost their seats.  Of 15 legislators whose reelection was a priority
for the League of Conservation
Voters, seven lost.
<P>
 <li>New freshmen were elected on
platforms to reform or repeal laws like the Endangered
Species and Clean Water Acts. 
They include Republicans Ed Brant of Tennessee,
Helen Chenoweth of Idaho, Wes Cooley
of Ohio, John Shadegg of Arizona, Linda
Smith of Washington, and William &quot;Mac&quot;
Thornberry of
Texas.  Indiana voters elected David McIntosh,
the former executive director of Vice President Dan Quayle's
Council on Competitiveness,
an agency that infuriated environmental lobbyists with its deregulatory
initiatives.<BR>
</ul>
<P><a name="unholy"></a>
<B>THE &quot;UNHOLY TRINITY&quot;</B>
<P>
 Dissatisfaction with much current government environmental regulation
centers on three issues--risk assessment, unfunded mandates, and
property rights.  They have been dubbed the &quot;unholy trinity&quot;
or the &quot;triple threat&quot; by environmental lobbyists. 
Environmental groups consider them the greatest threat to their
legislative and regulatory agendas, short of wholesale budget
cuts or the repudiation of government regulation as an environmental
protection strategy.
<P>
<ul>
<li><I>Risk
Assessment</I>--The premise underlying much federal environmental
regulation is that people's lives can be made safer by eliminating
or reducing human exposure to any number of dangerous substances--from
industrial air emissions to household chemicals.  But instead
of focusing on genuine, i.e., scientifically demonstrable, threats
to public health and safety,  the regulatory process often targets
risks that the public fears most or that have public relations
or political value.  Federal agencies spend millions
of dollars that do comparatively little to improve public health
and environmental quality.  According to analysts at Harvard's
School of Public Health, the cost-per-life-saved of the average
EPA regulation--over $7.5
million--is 87 times higher than the cost-per-life-saved of an
average regulation issued by the Occupational
Safety and Health Administration.  Moreover, some
federal regulations make the questionable scientific assumption
that any dose of a substance found to be toxic in certain dosages
and under certain conditions must therefore always be considered
dangerous to human health.  But a central principle of toxicology
is &quot;the dose makes the poison.&quot;
<P>
 Critics of agencies like EPA
are demanding more openness about the methods used to draft environmental
regulations.  They say that decisionmaking would improve if agencies
had to rely on peer-reviewed science and conducted cost-benefit
analysis of proposed regulations.  &quot;Such analysis permits
comparison of various options, all of which may be beneficial
in some way, but not all of which can be simultaneously taken,&quot;
explains environmental analyst Kent Jeffreys.
<P>
 Some environmentalists agree in principle.  According to former
National Audubon Society president
Peter Berle, &quot;Clearly it is a useful
way of establishing priorities.  We've got to ask ourselves whether
[policies] make sense from a cost point of view.&quot;
 Nonetheless, all major environmental groups formally oppose requiring
agencies to perform risk assessments and cost-benefit analyses
on the grounds that such analyses are &quot;pseudo-scientific.&quot;
<P>
 <li><I>Unfunded
Mandates</I>--Congress creates an &quot;unfunded mandate&quot;
when it passes a law that requires state or local governments
to meet goals or create programs, but fails to provide the money
for its implementation.  Under pressure to reduce the federal
deficit, Congress has increasingly relied
on them to meet environmental goals.
<P>
 State and local officials naturally oppose unfunded mandates
because their local priorities must be subordinated to Washington's
dictates.  Currently, it is estimated that up to 12 percent of
municipal revenues are spent to comply with unfunded mandates
of all sorts.  Local concerns are well-articulated by Michael
J. Pompilli, head of the environmental
health division of the Columbus, Ohio,
Health Department: &quot;What bothers me is that the new rules
coming out of Washington are taking money from decent programs
and making me waste them on less important problems.  It kills
you as a city official to see this kind of money spent for nothing.&quot;
<P>
 <li><I>Property
Rights</I>--Many environmental regulations override private land-use
decisions.  For example, the Fish
&amp; Wildlife Service will routinely deny property owners use
of their land if endangered species are present.  Policies to
protect wetlands and scenic rivers also supersede private property
rights.
<P>
 Many landowners say these policies violate the &quot;takings
clause&quot; of the Fifth Amendment to the U.S.
Constitution, which states &quot;. . . nor shall private property
be taken for public use without just compensation.&quot;  Property
rights advocates would reinvigorate this provision of the Bill
of Rights.  If the public wants to protect endangered species
or preserve a scenic vista, they say the public should be willing
to pay for it, just as it pays for highways, military bases, parks,
and other &quot;public goods.&quot;
<P>
</ul>
 Washington environmental lobbyists steadfastly oppose risk assessment,
relief from unfunded mandates, and greater protection of property.
 Thus, the Natural Resources
Defense Council announced that opposing such proposals would be
its &quot;single most important environmental campaign ever.&quot;
 The Sierra Club's executive director calls
these three issues &quot;pure and simple, an overt and calculated
attack on the environment,&quot; and &quot;an assault on the guiding
principle of virtually all laws governing air, water, and waste
disposal.&quot;  Most Americans, however, do not
appear to agree.  Indeed, many support these reforms while strongly
favoring environmental protection.  To most Americans, the two
are not incompatible.

<P><a name="envi"></a>
<B>ENVIRONMENTAL BACKLASH AND THE 103RD CONGRESS</B>
<P>
 The extent of the backlash against environmentalists can be seen
in the record of the 103rd Congress (1993-1994).  As environmentalists
see it, that Congress was an unmitigated
disaster.  The League of
Conservation Voters rated it the worst in 25 years.  Although
environmental lobbyists expected much from a Democratic President
and Congress, only one notable bill was signed into law, the California
Desert Protection Act.  Despite environmentalist cries of urgency,
Congress was unable to reauthorize several expired environmental
laws.
<P>
 Partisan gridlock is how pundits have explained Congressional
inaction: Republicans and conservative Democrats from the South
and West blocked good bills to placate industry lobbyists or for
partisan advantage.  EPA
Administrator Carol Browner told journalists,
&quot;What we've run into is gridlock and obstructionism that
is truly unprecedented.&quot;
<P>
 This argument may work in other areas, but not for environmental
legislation.  Little was attempted on the House
or Senate floor that culminated in gridlock.
 Rather, back room agreements were reached between influential
liberal legislators and the representatives of Washington's largest
environmental groups that doomed passage of the reauthorization
bills that environmentalists claimed they wanted.
<P>
 In February 1994, the representatives of six major environmental
groups--the Natural Resources
Defense Council, the Sierra Club, the National
Audubon Society, the National
Wildlife Federation, the Friends of
the Earth, and the Environmental
Defense Fund--met with California Democratic Representatives George
Miller, then-chairman of the House
Natural Resources Committee, and Henry Waxman,
then-chairman of the Environment
subcommittee of the House Energy and Commerce Committee, to discuss
legislative strategy.  Because they anticipated that serious efforts
would be made to attach &quot;unholy trinity&quot; amendments
to upcoming environmental legislation, the lobbyists decided it
was better to hold off on consideration of any important environmental
bills.  They thought they had the strength to stop bills from
moving, but not enough to defeat the hostile amendments.  As Jim
Maddy, former president of the League
of Conservation Voters later explained, &quot;The best we can
do is prevent Congress from weakening the Clean
Water Act, prevent this Congress from weakening Superfund,
prevent this Congress from weakening the Safe
Drinking Water Act and prevent this Congress from weakening the
Endangered Species Act.&quot;
<P>
 This decision was documented in an extremely controversial memo
leaked on Capitol Hill in March 1994.  Written by
the NRDC's chief lobbyist,
Erik Olson, the memo outlined &quot;the legislative
agenda for this Congress&quot; on environmental issues as determined
at the lobbyists' meeting with Miller and Waxman.  The memo explained
that &quot;kill strategies&quot; were to be adopted for environmental
legislation that was susceptible to amendments of the kind that
the memo labeled &quot;unholy trinity.&quot;  Reauthorization
of the nation's solid waste law--the Resource
Conservation and Recovery Act, or RCRA--and the Endangered
Species Act were to be &quot;taken off the table.&quot;  A &quot;kill
strategy&quot; was also intended for the reauthorization of the
Clean Water Act.  National
Audubon Society vice president Brock Evans
later described the strategy: &quot;We are slowing down on some
of our agenda because it is just too risky to reauthorize the
<!--Endangered Species Act of 1973,-->Endangered Species Act,
for example, with all these amendments locked into it.&quot;
<P>
 The only bill the group decided to allow on the floor was the
reauthorization of the Safe Drinking
Water Act.  Because it applies primarily to municipal water systems,
the lobbyists presumed it would attract less industry interest
and would more easily be kept free of reform amendments.  Yet
Olson and the others did not appreciate the
extent of opposition to their agenda.  They did not realize that
their primary opponent was no longer industry.  As one Senate
staffer explained, the &quot;primary adversary on many of these
issues isn't the National
Association of Manufacturers--it's the National
Governors' Association.&quot;
<P>
 As a result of the miscalculation the strategy failed.  The Senate
approved hostile unholy trinity amendments and proceeded to pass
the Safe Drinking Water Act reauthorization
by a large margin.  Even though a &quot;clean&quot; bill emerged
from the House, environmental
lobbyists recognized that an agreement with the Senate to strip
the offending provisions could not be reached and opted to let
the bill die before a House-Senate conference rather than allow
it to be enacted into law.  Thus even a relatively non-controversial
bill--it passed by wide majorities in both Houses of Congress--was
killed by environmental lobbyists opposed to the &quot;unholy
trinity.&quot;
<P>
 Environmental lobbyists have blamed this and other failures on
special interest groups who &quot;profit from pollution and from
exploiting public lands and resources.&quot;  A joint letter,
characterized as a &quot;Fourth of July 'wakeup call',&quot; was
signed by fifteen environmental lobbying organizations.  They
charged that &quot;At every turn, members of Congress are getting
more pressure from those who want to weaken environmental laws
than from those who want to strengthen them.&quot;
 The letter, sent to 400,000 people on the mailing lists of the
participating groups, was meant to revive grass roots activism
and offered a &quot;citizen action guide&quot; with counter-arguments
on &quot;unholy trinity&quot; issues.  One House aide explained
the approach, &quot;Without local-level support, there's no reason
for congressional moderates to vote with the environment.&quot;
<P>
 Neither lack of effort nor misallocation of resources explains
why the environmental movement failed to pass its legislative
agenda.  Rather, the leaders of environmental groups misunderstood
public sentiment.  Looking at polling data showing broad support
for environmental protection, they assumed the public must support
the agenda of the National
Wildlife Federation, the Sierra Club and the
League of Conservation Voters.
 But the same polls often show public support for reforms such
as the compensation of property owners for the adverse impact
of land-use regulations intended to protect wetlands or endangered
species.
<P>
 Environmentalists do not see that the public's interest in economic
common sense and fairness is compatible with support for a clean
environment.  Senate
Environment Committee staffer Michael Evans
tried explaining this at a seminar organized by the League
of Conservation Voters: &quot;Each of [the &quot;unholy trinity&quot;]
issues embodies a core truth.  It's important for you to concede
the truth, embrace it.  That's what's happening on the other side.
 They concede the principle of environmental protection, and they
talk about the need to prioritize resources.&quot;<BR>

<P><a name="increasing"></a>
<B>INCREASING PUBLIC DISSATISFACTION</B>
<P>
 Environmentalism's political failures coincide with a decline
in public support for Washington's environmental establishment.
 Since 1990, the ten largest environmental groups have lost members
and their annual revenues have been stagnant.  After a decade
of tremendous expansion, the ten largest groups--Ducks
Unlimited, the Environmental
Defense Fund, Greenpeace, Inc., the National
Audubon Society, the National
Parks and Conservation Association, the National
Wildlife Federation, the Sierra Club, the Nature
Conservancy, the Wilderness Society,
and the World Wildlife Fund--saw their
collective membership drop 6.5 percent from 1990 to 1993.
 &quot;It was easy for environmental groups to raise money&quot;
in the 1970s and 1980s, explains Dan <!--Borochoff, Dan,-->Borochoff
of the <!--American Institute of Philanthropy,-->American Institute
of Philanthropy, &quot;Now they're having to justify themselves
more.&quot;
<P>
 Worse, the problems are not just financial.  &quot;The green
groups also are faced with widespread cynicism about institutions
in general&quot; and public distrust of Washington, D.C.
 When Cindy Gabriel learned that former
National Wildlife Federation
president Jay Hair,  earned over $230,000 per year,
she told <I>The </I><I>Wall Street
Journal</I> she probably would quit the organization.
 If she saw the salaries of the other environmental C.E.O.s, Ms.
Gabriel might never contribute again to a national environmental
lobbying group.  Many environmental leaders are paid like high-powered
inside-the-beltway lobbyists, which is what they have become:
<P>
 <ul>
<li> Jay D. Hair
(former president), National
Wildlife Federation ($242,060);
<P>
<li>Fred Krupp,
Environmental Defense Fund ($213,504);
<P>
 <li> Kathryn Fuller,
<!--World Wildlife Fund,-->World Wildlife Fund ($185,000);
<P>
<li> Peter A.A. Berle
(former president), National Audubon
Society ($171,154);
<P>
<li> Karin Sheldon,
Wilderness Society ($90,896);
<P>
<li> Carl Pope,
Sierra Club ($77,142);
<P>
<li> Barbara Dudley,
Greenpeace ($65,000).
</ul>
<P>
 Left-liberal critics like writers for <I>The </I><I>Nation</I>
take particular exception: &quot;The mainstream high brass is
elitist, highly paid, detached from the people, indifferent to
the working class and a firm ally of big government.&quot;
 A recent controversy inside the Sierra Club
about logging in the Northern Rockies is illustrative.  Local
chapters in Montana and other states have called for an end to
logging on federal lands there.  But the Sierra Club's national
leadership has opposed such a blanket policy, and responded by
threatening to depose local elected officials.  &quot;What we
are seeing here is how an environmental organization becomes a
bureaucracy,&quot; said Andy Mahler, a Sierra
Club member in Indiana.  &quot;The higher up in the organization
you go, the impulse is to protect each other, to protect funding,
to protect political access rather than take a stand.&quot;
<P>
 A study from the Center
for the Study of American Business confirms the suspicion that
environmental organizations have become more bureaucratic over
the past two decades.  Authors Christopher Boerner
and Jennifer Chilton Kallery
find that staffs at the major groups have skyrocketed since 1970.
 The most rapid growth occurred in the 1980s, with many employees
working in fundraising and membership development.  Some groups
may devote as much as 25 percent of revenues to fundraising and
20 percent more to membership development.  &quot;Such hefty investments
in promotion and development by [some] environmental groups have
almost certainly been primary contributors to their growth over
the last fifteen years,&quot; they note.
<P>
 Dave Foreman, a former Wilderness
Society lobbyist and founder of Earth First!
and The Wildlands Project speaks with
characteristic fervor:<BR>

<P>
<blockquote> As in most business, government, and citizen organizations,
the technicians--accountants, lawyers, public-relations-experts,
and political pros--have taken over from the idealists. . . .
 Political operatives, not conservationists, are sought for jobs
with environmental groups. . . .  A salaried elite has formed
that elevates itself above the volunteers.
</blockquote>
<P>
 This concern is summed up by Bill Gifford
and the editors of <I>Outside</I> magazine: &quot;If
only some of the larger groups didn't have vast bureaucracies,
publicity machines, and presidents like the National
Wildlife Federation's Jay Hair, who is accustomed
to being squired about by a chauffeur.&quot;
<P>
 When the <I>Chronicle of Philanthropy</I>
polled attitudes toward charity it found that no environmental
organization made the public's list of the twenty &quot;Best Liked&quot;
or &quot;Most Credible&quot; charitable causes.
But the twenty &quot;Most Opposed&quot; groups included Greenpeace
(6th), the Sierra Club (12th), and the Environmental
Defense Fund (20th).  Among the twenty &quot;Least Credible&quot;
were the same three organizations--7th, 14th, and 18th--and Friends
of the Earth Foundation (19th).  Greenpeace,
the National Audubon Society and
the Sierra Club were also on the list of top
twenty &quot;never donated to&quot; charitable causes.  Similarly,
a poll conducted by <!--American Forests,--><I>American Forests</I>
found that in the northwestern United States environmentalists
are less trusted than timber industry scientists.
<P>
 Changing public attitudes toward environmental lobbyists hurts
some groups more than others.  Four groups have been hit hard
by falling memberships and revenues: the Sierra
Club, the National Audubon Society,
the Wilderness Society, and Greenpeace.
<P>
<ul>
<li> <I>Sierra
Club</I>--From 1990 to 1993, membership fell from almost 630,000
to 500,000.  In one year, 1992-1993, membership dropped
15 percent.  Sierra has accumulated deficits of almost
$3 million since 1990.  The Sierra Club recently announced plans
to reduce its coverage of policy issues.  In 1995, it will focus
on pollution prevention and scenic preservation, and drop work
on population issues, energy conservation and other issues.  The
Club plans to cut its budget by $3.7 million and lay off 350 employees.
 As Sierra Club executive director Carl <!--Pope, Carl,-->Pope
explained, &quot;We had been spending our reserves but no longer
felt this was prudent.&quot;
<P>
<li><I>National
Audubon Society</I>--Membership dropped by 8 percent from 1992
to 1993, and donations also slipped slightly.  Membership
growth has waned since Audubon refashioned its image as an activist
group.  In 1993, it ran a $1.7 million deficit. 
Audubon officials hope to balance their budget by 1996.
<P>
<li><I>Wilderness
Society</I>--Membership plummeted by nearly a third between 1990
and 1993 and finances dropped by $2.9 million--almost
one-sixth.  Field offices were closed in Oregon,
Utah, and Maine.  Society staffers &quot;now must plunk down a
quarter for office coffee.&quot;
<P>
<li><I>Greenpeace</I>--In
1990, Greenpeace had approximately 2.5 million members, but membership
has dropped by 800,000.  Greenpeace's funding dropped
by nearly a third in 1991.  Revenues for Greenpeace
dropped by nearly 10 percent more between 1992 and 1993,
forcing the group to lay off 100 staff members.  Explains Greenpeace's
development director, David <!--Lemos, David,-->Lemos, &quot;We
had gotten used to having a lot more money.&quot;
</ul>
<P>
 Not all environmental groups have done poorly in the 1990s. 
The Environmental Defense Fund
(EDF) had increases in membership (25 percent) and revenues (6
percent) between 1992 and 1993.  The World
Wildlife Fund (WWF) lost 7 percent of its members during the period,
but revenues increased 10 percent.  Donations may
not be dramatically increasing at the Nature
Conservancy (TNC), but <I>Outside</I> magazine
characterizes its finances as &quot;cash-flow heaven.&quot;
<P>
 EDF, WWF and TNC benefit from perceptions of them as more conservative
than other environmental advocacy organizations.  Bush EPA chief
William Reilly was tapped from the ranks
of WWF, and the Administration's 1990 Clean
Air Act proposal borrowed heavily from the work of EDF.  Unlike
most environmental groups, TNC eschews high-profile lobbying campaigns.
 To promote conservation, it directs most of its resources towards
the purchase of lands and easements.
<P>
 Still, the fortunes of environmental groups may be tied, at least
in part, to the health of the economy.  Charitable giving tends
to increase in times of economic prosperity.  &quot;Giving by
individuals and corporations jumped dramatically in the 1980s&quot;
explains economist Richard B. McKenzie.
 Private charitable giving, which increased by less than 3.5 percent
per year from 1955 to 1980, increased over 5.1 percent annually
during the 1980s, from $77.5 billion in 1980 to over $120 billion
in 1989.  When the economy slowed in 1989, the rise in charitable
giving came to a standstill and began to rise only after the economy
picked-up in 1991.
<P>
 This trend certainly affects the finances of environmental groups.
 Boerner and Kallery
found a correlation between per capita GNP and organizational
membership and revenue when they examined the Wilderness
Society, Sierra Club, National
Audubon Society, Natural
Resources Defense Council and the Nature
Conservancy.  Moreover, polling data showed that
support for environmental policy tracks economic concerns.  A
1992 survey found that 80 percent of the public agreed with the
statement &quot;protecting the environment is so important that
requirements and standards cannot be too high, and continuing
environmental improvements must be made regardless of cost.&quot;
 Yet in 1993, only 58 percent agreed with the statement.<SUP>67</SUP>
<P>
 Another factor is political leadership.  Environmentalists certainly
credit Reagan Interior Secretary James Watt
and EPA Administrator Anne Gorsuch for their
own good fortune in fundraising.  As the radical <I>Nation</I>
columnist Alexander Cockburn and <I>Wild
Forest Review</I> editor Jeffrey St.
Clair argue: &quot;The venal but entirely harmless Watt was a
bankbook extravaganza to the mainstream environmental groups,
who sold him as Genghis incarnate.  Memberships doubled, budgets
tripled.  Everyone packed up, hired C.E.O.s at six-figure salaries
and moved to spacious quarters in D.C.&quot;
<P>
 The <I>Exxon Valdez</I> spill also filled
environmentalist coffers.  The dramatic spill off Alaska's coast
&quot;just really presented an opportunity,&quot; said Keller
Ries of the National
Wildlife Federation.  In 1990 membership for some groups, such
as Greenpeace and the Sierra
Club, peaked.  &quot;We're in the ironic situation where possibly
the nation's greatest environmental catastrophe ever is causing
this increased interest in environmental organizations,&quot;
noted Robert SanGeorge of the National
Audubon Society.
<P>
 The reverse may be happening now.  Susan Carson,
a former National Audubon Society
staffer told <I>The </I><I>Wall Street
Journal</I> that environmental groups are suffering from the &quot;Gore
effect.&quot;  &quot;The basic theory is that with Gore and Clinton
in power, the environmental shtick is being handled,&quot; she
says.  Environmental leaders think both economics
and politics are at work.  &quot;The No. 1 cause of our problems
has been the economy,&quot; said Ben Beach,
a Wilderness Society spokesman.  &quot;When
the economy went down, so did our membership.  The election of
Clinton and Gore
also didn't help.  Some people believed there was less need to
support environmental causes.&quot;
<P>
 Environmental groups have begun demonizing their opponents to
revive their sources of support.  The July 1994 joint fundraising
appeal signed by fifteen groups charged that &quot;even during
the Reagan / Watt / Gorsuch years, we have never faced such a
serious threat to our environmental laws in Congress.&quot;  Since
the November 1994 election, the rhetoric has sharpened.  Wilderness
Society president Jon Roush signed a fundraising
appeal claiming that &quot;Today, the Wilderness Society must
adapt to a new climate that flings storms of opposition against
our efforts to conserve America's precious natural heritage.&quot;
 The Sierra Club labeled the regulatory reform
proposals in the Republican &quot;Contract
With America&quot; a &quot;polluter's bill of rights&quot; and
an undeclared &quot;war on the environment.&quot;
<P>
 Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, a former
President of the League of
Conservation Voters, explained the fundraising tactics of environmental
lobbying organizations.<BR>

<P>
<blockquote> The bottom line for the environmentalists is how
do you induce people to send money to sustain the movement. .
. .  For years and years, they said, &quot;James Watt is out to
destroy life on Earth as we know it--send money.&quot;  &quot;The
Exxon Valdez just crashed--send money.&quot;  The game has changed.
 It's a lot harder now to begin the sentence that ends with &quot;Send
money.&quot;
</blockquote>
<P>
<B>OUTLINE</B>
<P>
 The environmental movement is at a crossroads.  Once environmental
groups made consistent strides towards ambitious policy objectives.
 Today, environmentalists are running into a brick wall.  Assorted
items on the environmentalist agenda face a variety of opponents
in statehouses and in the U.S. Congress,
and green fundraising has started to lag.  Can America's environmental
establishment overcome its recent failures?  Or will American
environmentalism take a new course?
<P>
 This book will survey recent developments that are affecting
environmental groups.  They are suffering declining memberships,
declining political fortunes, and the challenge posed by a so-called
&quot;environmental backlash.&quot;  But they remain a formidable
power in the world of Washington special interest lobbies.
<P>
 Chapter One reviews the &quot;first wave&quot; of environmental
groups--the conservation organizations that focused on land, resource
and wildlife conservation.  It examines their increasing reliance
on centralized federal regulation and government land ownership
to achieve their objectives.
<P>
 Chapter Two focuses on the &quot;second wave&quot; of groups
that were, almost literally, the products of Earth
Day 1970.  These groups were activists from the start, and they
launched the environmental movement's attack on modern industrial
society and its assault on the use of chemicals and advanced technologies.
<P>
 Chapter Three is on international environmentalism, from the
concept of &quot;sustainable development&quot; to the push for
population control.  The growing presence of American environmental
groups in the international arena is explored.
<P>
 Chapter Four analyzes the role environmental groups play in developing
public policies and shaping public opinion on environmental issues.
 It includes a look at the environmental curriculum in the schools
and discusses how environmental lobbyists exert influence in the
Clinton Administration.
<P>
 Chapter Five surveys where environmental groups get financial
support--from individuals, foundations and corporations--and describes
how environmental groups are trying to diversify their funding
base through government grants and the sale of commercial products.
<P>
 Chapter Six discusses emerging movements within environmentalism:
from the deep ecology movement and the environmental justice movement
to free market environmentalism and the property rights and &quot;wise-use&quot;
environmental backlash.
<P>
 Finally, appendices analyze the largest and most influential
environmental organizations operating in America today, their
sources of income, officers, and most important activities.<BR>

</BODY>

</HTML>
</DOC>
