<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Rise of the Nanny State -- CRC</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/crc/images/bg.gif">
<a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation Bar" border="0" align="left" ISMAP></a>
<blockquote>
<img src="/crc/images/nanny.gif" alt="Book Cover" align="right">
<P>
<h2> The Rise of the Nanny State: How Consumer Advocates Try to Run Our Lives</h2>
(<a href="/crc/about/pubs.html">Ordering Information</a>)<br><P>
<a href="#summ">Executive Summary</a>
<P>
<h3>Table of Contents</h3>
<ul>
Preface
<P>
<b>Introduction</b> An Age of Maturity
<P>
<b>Chapter One</b> From <I>The Jungle</I> to the Great Society
<P>
<b>Chapter Two</b> Naderites and Lawyers
<P>
<b>Chapter Three</b> Food and Science:  Creating a Pseudo-Crisis
<P>
<b>Chapter Four</b> Consumer Nannyism:  Label Madness and the New Puritanism
<P>
<b>Chapter Five</b> The Anti-Destination League
<P>
<b>Chapter Six</b> Consumerists and Government Medicine
<P>
<b>Chapter Seven</b>How to Restrain Big Nanny Government
<P>
Appendices
<P>
I.  Action on Smoking and Health
<P>
II. Center for Auto Safety
<P>
III. Center for Science in the Public Interest
<P>
IV. Center for Study of Responsive Law
<P>
V. Consumer Federation of America
<P>
VI. Consumers Union of the United States
<P>
VII. Fund for Public Interest Research
<P>
IX. National Consumers League
<P>
X. Public Citizen Foundation/Public Citizen, Inc.
<P>
XI. Public Voice for Food and Health Policy
<P>
XII. Trial Lawyers for Public Justice, P.C.
<P>
XIII. U.S. Public Interest Research Group
<P>
XIV. Public Financial Disclosure Reports:  CPSC Chairman Ann Brown
and CPSC Vice Chairman Mary Gall
</ul>
<P>
<a name="summ"></a>

<h3>Executive Summary</h3>
<i>The Rise of the Nanny
State</i> examines the origins, goals, and activities of the modern
consumer movement--a movement that, in the words of Capital Research
Center Visiting Fellow Tom Holt, &quot;does not address the needs
of consumers.  
<P>
Instead, it serves the bureaucratic interests of
governing elites and the ideological and organizational interests
of the movement itself.&quot; Holt paints a decidedly unflattering
portrait of the consumer movement.  As the recent Alar scare showed,
consumer advocates capitalize on the public's ignorance of science
and the media's eagerness for calamity.  Under the guise of public
health and safety, they seek to justify regulations dictating
their idea of the public good to our households and workplaces.
<P>
 With few exceptions, they advocate bigger and more intrusive
government and are hostile to free markets and personal responsibility.
Holt shows that the consumer movement has imposed significant
costs on industry--costs ultimately passed on to consumers--and
has violated individual freedoms in a futile effort to protect
us from our own actions and judgment.  Based on his analysis,
he calls for: major tort reform; the abolition of CAFE standards
and the Delaney clause; a reduced federal role in health care;
a major overhaul of the Consumer Product Safety Commission; and
other reforms of regulatory agencies.
</ul>
</blockquote>
</BODY>

