<HTML>
<title>Brzonkala Press Release -- CIR</title>
<HEAD>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><H2>Center For Individual Rights</H2>

<H3>1300 NINETEENTH STREET, N.W., SUITE 260<BR>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20036<BR></h3>

(202) 833-8400<BR>
FAX: (202) 833-8410<BR>
<A HREF="mailto:CIR@mail.wdn.com">CIR@MAIL.WDN.COM</A><BR>
</CENTER><BR>
July 29, 1996<BR><BR>
<blockquote>

          <H2>   <CENTER> Federal Court Finds Violence Against
                   Women Act Unconstitutional</CENTER></H2>

 <P>    In a case which has received national attention, Federal
Judge Jackson Kiser declared the Violence Against Women Act
(VAWA) unconstitutional.

<P>     VAWA, which passed as part of the omnibus crime bill of
1994, created a federal civil action for crimes motivated by
"discriminatory animus" against gender.  In passing VAWA,
Congress created a broad new federal tort for crimes which
traditionally have fallen under state jurisdiction.

<P>     In <EM>Brzonkala v. Virginia Polytechnic Institute</EM>, a
student at Virginia Tech filed suit under VAWA against two members of
the Virginia Tech football team--Antonio Morrison and James
Crawford--for
 an alleged rape.  A Virginia Federal Court found Friday that
Congress did not have constitutional authority to enact VAWA,
which if implemented would have the effect of "excessively
extending Congress's power and of inappropriately tipping the
balance [of power] away from the states."  Judge Kiser emphasized the
importance of the issues at stake in warning that "[Congress']
authority to act is limited by the Constitution, and the
constitutional limits must be respected if our federal system is to
survive."

<P>     The court's decision to strike down VAWA has the added
benefit of dismissing federal lawsuits against what by all
accounts are two innocent men.  Defendants Morrison and Crawford
were cleared of rape charges by both the Virginia Tech campus
disciplinary body and the state grand jury, yet still faced
federal VAWA charges for a complaint made over seven months after the
alleged rape, by an accuser who was unable to identify them
accurately.

 <P>    Michael E. Rosman, co-counsel for Antonio Morrison and
General Counsel for the Center for Individual Rights, stated that "We
are delighted with the outcome of this case and believe that Judge
Kiser's opinion, by dint of its reasoning and careful analysis, will
influence many courts on this same issue."  Mr. Morrison is also
represented by W. David Paxton and M. Christina Floyd of the Roanoke
firm of Gentry, Locke, Rakes & Moore.  Mr. Crawford is represented by
Joseph Graham Painter, Jr., a solo practioner in Blackbury, Virginia.

<P>     To receive a copy of the decision, or for more information
about the case, call Robert Alt, Director of Public Relations and
Education for the Center for Individual Rights, at 202-833-8400, ext.
101.
</blockquote>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
