<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Columbia Union College - Complaint</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<PRE>

             UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT FOR
                THE DISTRICT OF MARYLAND
                    Greenbelt  Division

COLUMBIA UNION COLLEGE,
                       plaintiff,

v. 

MARYLAND HIGHER EDUCATION
 COMMISSION,
   -and-
MARYLAND BOARD OF
PUBLIC WORKS
   -and-
J. JOSEPH CURRAN, JR.
 in his official capacity as
 Attorney General of Maryland
   -and-
WILLIAM F. HOWARD
 in his official capacity as
 Assistant Attorney General of
 Maryland
   -and-
DOROTHY DIXON CHANEY,
DONNA R. CUNNINGHAME,
OSBORNE A. PAYNE,
CHARLES B. SAUNDERS, JR.,
RICHARD P. STREET, JR.,
ALBERT NATHANIEL WHITING,
HONORABLE J. GLENN BEALL, JR.,
EDWARD O. CLARKE, JR.,
TERRY L. LIERMAN,
R. KATHLEEN PERINI,
TERRA N. SMITH,
CONSTANCE CORNELL, and
JOHN L. GREEN,
   in their official capacities
   as Members of the Maryland
   Higher Education Commission
                              Defendants,

                         COMPLAINT

               NATURE AND SUMMARY OF THE ACTION

1. This is a civil action for declaratory and injunctive relief
arising from defendants' violation of plaintiff's constitutional
and civil rights and liberties under the United States
Constitution and federal law. 

2.   Plaintiff COLUMBIA UNION COLLEGE, a private college
affiliated with the Seventh-day Adventist Church, seeks:
  
(a)  a declaration that the conduct of the defendants in
applying and administering the Father Sellinger Program for
the State of Maryland, which denies plaintiff the same benefits
(including, but not limited to, eligibility to receive financial
aid paid to Maryland schools of higher education) granted other
similarly situated colleges and universities, and which denies
plaintiff such funds solely and expressly because of the content
or viewpoint of plaintiff's speech and beliefs, violates
plaintiffs rights to freedom of speech, freedom of association,
free exercise of religion, and to equal protection under the law,
as guaranteed by the First and Fourteenth Amendments to the
United States Constitution; 

(b)  a permanent order enjoining defendants from continuing to
apply a policy of discriminating against plaintiff in the
appropriation of Father Sellinger Program financial aid or in any
other manner on the basis of: the content or viewpoint of
plaintiff's speech and belief or on the basis of the content or
viewpoint of the speech of the Seventh-day Adventist Church with
which plaintiff is affiliated; its expression; its exercise of
religion; or its association;

(c)  such other relief as the Court deems just and proper.

                       JURISDICTION

3.   This action arises under the First and Fourteenth
Amendments to the United States Constitution.  Jurisdiction
over the claims is conferred on this Court by 28 U.S.C. Sections
1331 and 1343, by 42 U.S.C. Sections 1983, and by 42 U.S.C.
Section 2000bb-l(c). Plaintiff brings this action pursuant to 42
U.S.C. Section 1983, and claims all available relief pursuant to
that statute, including attorneys' fees under 42 U.S.C. Section
1998.

                            VENUE

4. Venue is proper in this Court pursuant to 28 U.S.C. Section
1391(b).

                           PARTIES

5. Plaintiff COLUMBIA UNION COLLEGE ("Columbia Union"), is a
private, four year college affiliated with the Seventh-day
Adventist Church located in Tacoma Park, Maryland in Montgomery
County.  Columbia Union was founded in 1904, and is and was at
all times relevant herein a four year college granting associate
and baccalaureate degrees in the liberal arts, sciences, and
certain professional fields.        

6.   Defendant the MARYLAND HIGHER EDUCATION COMMISSION (the
"Commission") was and is at all times relevant herein,
responsible for the implementation and administration of the
Father Sellinger Program, as set forth in Md. Code Edu. Ann,
Section 17-102, including the establishment of standards and
procedures for submitting applications for aid, verifying full
time equivalent student enrollment by institutions that apply
for aid, submitting reports or data on the use of Father
Sellinger Program funds by the institutions that receive it, and
paying the aid to the institutions during the fiscal year. The
Commission's actions are subject to review by the Maryland Board
of Public Works.

7.   Defendant MARYLAND BOARD OF PUBLIC WORKS was and is at
all times relevant herein, responsible for review of the
Commission's actions.

8.   Defendant J. JOSEPH CURRAN, JR., sued in his capacity as
Attorney General for the State of Maryland, acting under the
authority of the Governor of Maryland, was an official
responsible for the actions taken under color of Maryland law,
that discriminated against Plaintiff Columbia Union.

9.   Defendant WILLIAM F. HOWARD, sued in his capacity as
Assistant Attorney General for the State of Maryland, acting on
behalf of the Attorney General of Maryland and under the
authority of the Governor of Maryland, was an official directly
responsible for acting under color of Maryland law, in
discriminating against Plaintiff Columbia Union.

10.  Defendant DOROTHY DIXON CHANEY, sued in her official
capacity as a member of the Commission, was an official directly
responsible for acting under color of Maryland law, in
discriminating against Plaintiff Columbia Union.

11.  Defendant DONNA H. CUNNINGHAME, sued in her official
capacity as a member of the Commission, was an official directly
responsible for acting under color of Maryland law, in
discriminating against Plaintiff Columbia Union.

12.  Defendant OSBORNE A. PAYNE, sued in his official capacity
as a member of the Commission, was an official directly
responsible for acting under color of Maryland law, in
discriminating against Plaintiff Columbia Union.

13.  Defendant CHARLES B. SAUNDERS, JR., sued in his official
capacity as a member of the Commission, was an official directly
responsible for acting under color of Maryland law, in
discriminating against Plaintiff Columbia Union.

14.  Defendant RICHARD P. STREET, JR., sued in his official
capacity as a member of the Commission, was an official directly
responsible for acting under color of Maryland law, in
discriminating against Plaintiff Columbia Union.

15.  Defendant ALBERT NATHANIEL WHITING, sued in his official
capacity as a member of the Commission, was an official directly
responsible for acting under color of Maryland law, in
discriminating against Plaintiff Columbia Union.

16.  Defendant HONORABLE J. GLENN BEALL, JR., sued in his
official capacity as a member of the Commission, was an official
directly responsible for acting under color of Maryland law, in
discriminating against Plaintiff Columbia Union.

17.  Defendant EDWARD O. CLARKE, JR., sued in his official
capacity as a member of the Commission, was an official directly
responsible for acting under color of Maryland law, in
discriminating against plaintiff Columbia Union.

18.  Defendant TERRY L. LIERMAN, sued in his official capacity
as a member of the Commission, was an official directly
responsible for acting under color of Maryland law, in
discriminating against Plaintiff Columbia Union. 

19.  Defendant R. KATHLEEN PERINI, sued in her official capacity
as a member of the Commission, was an official directly
responsible for acting under color of Maryland law, in
discriminating against Plaintiff Columbia Union.

20.  Defendant TERRA N. SMITH, sued in her official capacity
as a member of the Commission, was an official directly
responsible for acting under color of Maryland law, in
discriminating against Plaintiff Columbia Union.

21.  Defendant CONSTANCE CORNELL STUART, sued in her official
capacity as a member of the Commission, was an official directly
responsible for acting under color of Maryland law, in
discriminating against Plaintiff Columbia Union.

22.  Defendant JOHN L. GREEN, sued in his official capacity as a
member of the Commission, was an official directly responsible
for acting under color of Maryland law, in discriminating against
Plaintiff Columbia Union.

                      GENERAL ALLEGATIONS

23.  As provided for in the Code of Maryland, Education, Title
17, the Commission is charged with the authority to implement and
administer the Father Sellinger Program.  One of its
responsibilities is to receive and review applications for aid
and determine whether the institutions applying for aid are
eligible to receive Father Sellinger Program funds under the
criteria set forth in Md. Code Ann, Edu. Section 17-103.

24.  Md. Code Ann. Edu. Section 17-103 sets forth the following
eligibility requirements: 

1)  the institution must have been established prior to July 1,
1970; 2) it must be accredited by the State Department of
Education; 3) it must maintain more than one associate of arts or
baccalaureate degree programs; 4) it must submit for approval any
new programs or major alteration of programs to the Commission;
and 5) it must refrain from utilizing any of the money payable
under the Father Sellinger Program for sectarian purposes.

25.  Currently, and at all times relevant herein, the
Commission has set forth the guidelines and procedures for the
distribution of Father Sellinger Program funds to eligible
institutions.

26.  During the period relevant to this lawsuit, the Commission,
subject to the review of the Maryland Board of Public Works and
the recommendation of the Maryland Attorney General, regularly
distributed Father Sellinger Program Funds to colleges and
universities within Maryland.  Upon information and belief, this
practice dates back at least to 1957. 

27.  Upon information and belief, colleges and universities 
receiving Father Sellinger Program funds in the past have
included institutions that are affiliated with religions.  For
example, Mount St. Mary's College, Loyola University, and Notre
Dame College of Maryland have received Father Sellinger Program
funds and are affiliated with the Roman Catholic Church.  These
institutions are dedicated to the Catholic point of view and have
engaged in and continue to engage in sectarian activities and
expression. 

28.  In January 1990, Columbia Union submitted an application
to receive Father Sellinger Program funds to the Commission. 

29.  The application of Columbia Union for Father Sellinger
Program funds conformed with all applicable, content-neutral
Commission requirements.  In particular, Columbia Union was
established before July 1, 197O; it was then and is now
accredited by the State Department of Education; it maintains
numerous degree programs other than seminarian or theological
degrees; it agreed to submit any new programs or major program
alteration to the Commission for approval; and it agreed to use
Father Sellinger Program funds for non-sectarian purposes only.
                                
30.  On April 14, 1992, the Commission found that the college is
"pervasively sectarian" and denied Columbia Union's application
for aid. 

31.  The Commission offered no reason other than the alleged
status of Columbia Union as "pervasively sectarian" as a
basis to deny funding.

32.  On December 27, 1995, Dr. Charles Scriven, President of
Columbia Union, sought reconsideration of the Commission's
refusal to provide Columbia Union with Father Sellinger Program
Funds in light of the decision of the United States Supreme Court
in Rosenberger v. The Rector and Visitors at the University of
Virginia, 115 S. Ct. 2510 (1995).

33. On January 22, 1996, defendant William P. Howard, Assistant
Attorney General of Maryland, writing at the request of the
Commission, replied to Dr. Scriven's request, stating that
"unless the nature and practices of Columbia Union have changed
very substantially since 1992, I do not believe there would be
any point in pursuing a new application for private aid at this
time." 

34.  Defendants have denied, and, unless enjoined, will continue
to deny Father Sellinger Program funds to plaintiff solely and
expressly on the basis of plaintiff's viewpoint, content of its
expression, and the free exercise of religion by its faculty and
students. 

35.  Defendants cannot demonstrate a compelling interest
sufficient to justify the denial of Father Sellinger Program
funds to plaintiff, nor can defendants demonstrate that the
denial of funding is narrowly drawn to satisfy any such state
interest.

                     COUNT ONE: VIOLATION OF
                FREEDOM OF SPEECH AND ASSOCIATION

36.  The allegations contained in paragraphs 1 through 35
am incorporated herein by this reference.

37.  Although defendants have provided Father Sellinger Program
funding to a wide variety of colleges and universities that
engage in religious and secular expression, defendants have
illegally and unconstitutionally denied plaintiff Father
Sellinger Program funds based solely an the content or viewpoint
of plaintiffs speech, communications, identity, activities, or
affiliation.
 
38.  Plaintiff has unjustifiably and unlawfully been denied
benefits to which it was and is entitled as an eligible
institution as set forth in Maryland Code, Education, Title 17. 
This loss was the result of state action. This state action
violated and continues to violate plaintiff's rights of free
speech and free association under the First and Fourteenth
Amendments to the United States Constitution. The denial of
Father Sellinger Program funds to plaintiff constitutes
impermissible viewpoint and content discrimination. There exists
no compelling state interest to justify the defendants' actions. 
Moreover, even if there is some compelling state interest,
defendants actions are not narrowly tailored to achieve that
interest.

39.  The Commission's guidelines and definitions for allocating
Father Sellinger Program funds to institutions are unlawfully
vague in that persons of common intelligence must necessarily
guess at their meaning and differ as to their application, and
are also overbroad in that they reach constitutionally protected
activity.

40.  By virtue of the unlawful policies and conduct of
defendants, plaintiff has suffered and continues to suffer injury
to its rights of free speech, free association and free exercise
of religion, and to the furtherance of its lawful activities.

                 COUNT TWO: VIOLATION OF FREE
                     EXERCISE OE RELIGION

41.  The allegations contained in paragraphs 1 through 40
are incorporated herein by this reference.

42. The Free Exercise Clause of the First Amendment to the
United States Constitution prohibits government discrimination in
the allocation of benefits or imposition of burdens based upon an
individual's or group's religious beliefs, character, or
affiliation, or based upon the religious content of their
expression and is applicable to state action under the Fourteenth
Amendment. 

43.  Defendants impermissibly and unlawfully denied plaintiff
Father Sellinger Program funds generally available to other
Maryland colleges and universities. This denial was based upon
plaintiff's religious beliefs, character, affiliation, speech,
and association.

44.  Defendants have not shown and cannot show that denying
plaintiff Father Sellinger Program funds to which it is lawfully
entitled is necessary to serve a compelling state interest, nor
can defendants show that such a denial is a narrowly drawn
means of achieving that interest. 

45.  Defendants' conduct has deprived and continues to deprive
plaintiff of its right to free exercise of religion as guaranteed
under the First and Fourteenth Amendments to the United States
Constitution. 

46.  Defendants' conduct constitutes a failure to give reasonable
accommodation to plaintiff's religious beliefs.

47.  By virtue of the unlawful policies and conduct of the
defendants, plaintiff has suffered and continues to suffer injury
to its rights of religious freedom and to the furtherance of its
lawful activities.

                  COUNT THREE: VIOLATION OF EQUAL
                       PROTECTION OF THE LAWS

48.  The allegations contained in paragraphs 1 through 47 are
incorporated herein by this reference.

49.  By denying plaintiff the benefits to which other colleges
and universities are entitled, defendants unlawfully and
unconstitutionally have treated and continue to treat plaintiff
differently from other similarly situated colleges and
universities on the basis of the content or viewpoint of its
speech, association, beliefs, character, affiliation, identity,
and activity.

50.  By denying plaintiff the benefits that other colleges and
universities engaging in religious speech and activities receive
and have received, defendants unlawfully and unconstitutionally
treat plaintiff differently from other similarly situated
colleges and universities on the basis of its religious speech,
association, beliefs, character, affiliation, identity, and
activity. 

51.  Defendants' conduct under color of state law violates the
Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment to the United
States Constitution in that it constitutes discrimination on a
suspect basis and violates fundamental constitutional rights. 
This violation is not justified by a compelling state interest
and is not accomplished by narrowly drawn means. Defendants have
singled out plaintiff and denied it Father Sellinger Program
funds based upon the content or viewpoint of its affiliation, its
speech, its expression, and its association.

52.  Plaintiff has suffered and continues to suffer injury to its
rights of equal protection under the law, and to the furtherance
of its lawful activities, by virtue of the unlawful policies
and conduct of the defendants.

                      COUNT IV: VIOLATION OF
                 RELIGIOUS FREEDOM RESTORATION ACT

53.  The allegations contained in paragraphs 1 through 52 are
incorporated herein by this reference.

54.  Defendants impermissibly and unlawfully denied plaintiff
Father Sellinger Program funds generally available to other
Maryland colleges and universities.  This denial was based upon
plaintiff's religious beliefs, character, affiliation, speech,
and association.

55.  Defendants' denial of Father Sellinger Program funds to
plaintiff substantially burdens the free exercise of religion by
plaintiff and its students and faculty.

56.  Defendants have not shown and cannot show that denying
plaintiff Father Sellinger Program funds to which it is lawfully
entitled is necessary to serve a compelling state interest, nor
can defendants show that such a denial is a narrowly drawn means
of achieving that interest. 

57.  By virtue of the unlawful policies and conduct of the
defendants, plaintiff has suffered and continues to suffer injury
to its rights of religious freedom and to the furtherance of its
lawful activities, in violation of Religious Freedom Restoration
Act, 42 U.S.C. Sections 2000bb through 2000bb-4.

                     PETITION FOR RELIEF

58.  The allegations contained in paragraphs 1 through 57 are
incorporated herein by this reference.

59.  Plaintiff has no plain, speedy and adequate remedy at
law.

60.  Plaintiff is suffering, and will continue to suffer, 
irreparable injury for the period of the continued violation
of its constitutional rights. 

61.  Absent an injunction, defendants will continue to
violate Columbia Union's constitutional and statutory rights.

WHEREFORE, having stated claims against the defendants under the
United States Constitution and federal law, plaintiff petitions
this Court for the following relief:          

A.   a declaratory judgment that the conduct of the defendants in
establishing and applying a policy for the State of Maryland
which refuses to allow the same benefits to plaintiff as to other
similar colleges and universities (benefits including the receipt
of Father Sellinger Program funds) and which denies plaintiff
Father Sellinger Program funds solely and expressly because of
the content or viewpoint of its speech (1) violates plaintiffs
rights to freedom of speech, freedom of association, free
exercise of religion, and to equal protection under the law, as
guaranteed by the First and Fourteenth Amendments to the United
States Constitution, and (2) that such actions of defendants are
in violation of 42 U.S.C. Sections 2000bb et seq.;

B.   a permanent order enjoining the defendants from maintaining
and applying a policy of discrimination against plaintiff in the
appropriation of Father Sellinger Program funds or in any other
manner on the basis of plaintiff's speech or on the basis of the
content or viewpoint of the speech or the religion with which
plaintiff is affiliated;

C.  an order awarding plaintiff reasonable costs and attorneys'
fees pursuant to Section 2 of the Civil Rights Attorney's Fees
Award Act of 1976, as amended, 42 U.S.C. Section 1988 (1988); and

D. Such other relief as the court deems just and proper.

Respectfully submitted,

D. Alan Rudlin
R. Hewitt Pate
Sarah C. Johnson
HUNTON & WILLIAMS
951 East Byrd Street
Richmond, Virginia 23219
(804) 788-8200

