<title>Columbia Union College - Complaint - CIR</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><H2>Center For Individual Rights</H2><BR>

<H3>1300 NINETEENTH STREET, N.W., SUITE 260<BR>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20036<BR><BR>
    
(202) 833-8400<BR>
FAX: (202) 833-8410<BR>
<A HREF="mailto:CIR@mail.wdn.com">CIR@MAIL.WDN.COM</A></H3><BR>

June 12, 1996</CENTER><BR>


For Immediate Release<BR>



                  <CENTER>         <H2>CUC Claims Denial of Free Speech/Exercise of Religion</H2>
                             <H2> In Administration of Tuition Assistance Program</H2><BR></CENTER>


        
<P>        Columbia Union College filed a lawsuit in Federal Court Wednesday claiming that Maryland's
Higher Education Commission unconstitutionally discriminated against the college's religious viewpoint in
its administration of the Father Sellinger Program.  The program, established in 1971, provides state
funding to Maryland's private colleges--both religious and non-religious--to reduce tuition costs.

<P>        Columbia Union, a Seventh-day Adventist college located in Tacoma Park, Maryland, complies
with all state eligibility requirements for Sellinger funding, including a provision requiring recipients to
refrain from using funds for sectarian purposes.  Nevertheless, CUC was denied funding based upon the
commission's claim that the school is "pervasively religious," making it ineligible for funding due to
perceived church-state separation requirements arising from the First Amendment's Establishment
Clause.  Maryland has continued to deny CUC funding since its initial request in 1991, despite funding
other religious schools, including Mount St. Mary's College, Loyola University, and College of Notre
Dame of Maryland.

 <P>       CUC is challenging Maryland's decision, claiming that denial of funds on the basis of religious
viewpoint constitutes a violation of Free Speech and Free Exercise rights guaranteed by the First
Amendment, as well as the Religious Freedom Restoration Act.  This claim is supported by the Supreme
Court's 1995 decision in Rosenberger v. The Rector and Visitors of the University of Virginia, in which
the Court found the University of Virginia's refusal to grant funding to a student publication solely on the
basis of religious viewpoint violated the Free Speech guarantee of the First Amendment.

 <P>       Columbia Union is represented by R. Hewitt Pate of Hunton & Williams, and by the Center for
Individual Rights, a non-profit public interest law firm which represented the successful plaintiffs in
Rosenberger.

  <P>      Michael Rosman, General Counsel for the Center for Individual Rights declared:  "Maryland's
discrimination against Columbia Union violates the First and Fourteenth Amendments, the Religious
Freedom Restoration Act, and simply cannot be reconciled with the Supreme Court's decision in
Rosenberger.  We are pleased to represent CUC in this case."

  <P>      To receive a copy of the complaint, or for more information, please call Robert Alt, Director of
Public Affairs for the Center for Individual Rights, at 202-833-8400, ext. 101.
    
</body>
