<title>Docket Report: April 1996 -- CIR</title>
</HEAD>
<blockquote><blockquote>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/cir/pix/gavel2.gif">
<CENTER><img src="/cir/pix/docket.gif" alt="Docket Report">
<br>
<i> April 1996</i>
<p>
<small><a href="#index">Contents</a></small><br>
<H3>THE LAST LINE OF DEFENSE</H3>
</center>
<P>Publication of this extra-length <I>Docket Report</I> was delayed by the Fifth Circuit's momentous 
ruling in <I>Hopwood v. State of Texas</I>, our challenge to racial preferences in student admissions at the 
University of Texas Law School.  We won, and UT lost.  The defendants have asked for an emergency stay, 
arguing <I>inter alia</I> that the cessation of discrimination in student admissions would impose &quot;administrative 
burdens.&quot;  Details on the decision and its near-nuclear fallout on pages 2-5 of this <I>Report</I>.
<P>
<P>In addition to the <I>Hopwood</I> home run, we scored an anti-quota double.  In February, we settled 
a lawsuit against the National Science Foundation and Texas A &amp; M over selected-minorities-only 
summer study programs.  The defendants agreed to pay damages and fees and to desist from further race 
discrimination.  And in March, Ohio State University shelled out $368,000 to end our attack on OSU's 
minorities-only contracting program.  These matters having been settled, we teed up two additional 
race-exclusive programs with federal participation--one in Delaware, the other in Texas.
<P>
<P>In Ithaca, NY, Judge Rumsey of the New York Supreme Court (Tompkins County) heard oral 
arguments on Cornell University's motion to dismiss our lawsuit on behalf of Professor James B. Maas.  
While the motion is still pending, a Cornell faculty committee has concluded that the procedures under 
which Maas was sentenced were egregiously flawed, amply confirming our contention that Jim Maas got shafted.
<P>
<P>Speaking of which, we have agreed to represent two additional victims of the harassment craze.  
Cid Scallet was fired from his teaching job at the University of Virginia's Darden School of 
Management because the powers-that-be hated his politics.  Unable to find a legitimate reason for firing Scallet, 
Darden officials framed him for sexual harassment, the allegation being that Scallet modeled his socks 
provocatively in front of his class.  (No, we're not kidding). 
<P>
<P>More serious charges have been leveled against CIR client Antonio Morrison, a black student 
athlete at Virginia Polytechnic University:  a white female fellow-student has falsely accused Morrison 
of rape and has filed a lawsuit against against him, Virginia Tech, and other defendants.  The plaintiff 
has made a claim under the federal Violence Against Women Act of 1994, which penalizes crimes 
committed against women because of a discriminatory animus.  The &quot;proof&quot; of Morrison's mysogynist bias is 
his alleged failure to wear a condom during an assault he did not commit.
<P>
<P>The country has gone insane, but we're here to save it.  Evidence, as always, in these pages.

</blockquote>
