<img src="images/button.gif" alt="***" vspace=5 hspace=5>
<a href="#remark">A few Remarks about The Claremont Institute and its Work</a>

</dl>
<P>

<a name="mission">

<hr size=4 noshade>

<center>

   <H1>Our Mission</H1>

</center>

<hr size=4 noshade>

<P>

The Claremont Institute finds the answers to our nation's problems in the principles 
on which America was founded.  It upholds the ideas of liberty and equality.  It 
believes there can be no freedom and justice without a limited and accountable 
government that respects private property, promotes stable family life and maintains 
secure borders and a strong defense.

<P>

The Claremont Institute believes that an informed public can and will make the 
right choices for America's future.  Through its books, policy briefings and articles, 
its lectures, debates and seminars, the Institute engages Americans in an outgoing 
discussion about how they are governed and how their government can be improved.

<P>

Based in California, the Claremont Institute is a major force on the political 
landscape in the nation's largest and most pivotal state.  Its work is also national 
in scope: Institute studies have led to public outrage at the practices of Congress, 
public awareness of an ongoing attack on the American family and to significant 
change in environmental and property rights law.

<P>

The Institute's work is only beginning.  Today, our state and federal governments 
spend vast and increasing sums of public money for less and less good.  The 
public sector grows at the expense of the private.  Regulations intrude into every 
corner of our economic and private lives.  Schools no longer perform.  Police and 
courts no longer protect.  Good businesses are being driven to extinction by 
excessive and discriminatory controls and as a result good jobs continue to 
disappear.  Dependence grows and opportunity wanes with each passing year.

<P>

But America's Founders endowed our Republic with sound principles that bear on 
these problems and a framework for governing that is unmatched in the history of mankind.

<P>

The great conservative victories of 1994 can only be made lasting if they are 
guided by a return to these principles.  The work of the Claremont Institute, 
"the scholarship of the politics of freedom," has as its core these great principles.  
These victories have given the Claremont Institute a unique opportunity to advance 
the application of these principles of the founding to an important audience of 
reform-minded legislators.

<P>

Along with our on-going programs we have launched a series of strategic projects 
that will capitalize on these victories and ensure that the conservative realignment 
is a lasting one:

<P>

In conjunction with William F. Buckley's <i>National Review</i> magazine, the Institute 
publishes <i>National Review West</i>, an insert that goes to 80,000 conservatives in 
the western United States.  <i>NR West</i> features articles by the west's top 
conservatives on issues of state and national import.

<P>

Under the guidance of Distinguished Fellow William Rusher we are 
conducting a series of conferences entitled Project '96.  These 
conferences aim at deepening the debate among American conservatives 
about how to solve the most critical problems facing our country.  
These conferences will address welfare reform, the environment, 
federalism, and the breakdown of the American family.  

<P>

The Claremont Institute believes America's resources are greater than her 
problems.  Its mission is to restore the great principles on which our great 
nation was founded and to recover the institutions that proceed from them.  

<P>

<a name = "programs">

<hr size=4 noshade>

<center>

   <h1>Our Programs</h1>

</center>

<hr size=4 noshade>

<P>

The Claremont Institute is composed of four centers, each with a unique 
mission and a distinct responsibility.

<h4>The Golden State Center for Policy Studies</h4>

Through the Golden State Center in Sacramento, Claremont Institute 
scholars produce publications that educate public policy makers, the 
media, and interested citizens on California policy issues such as the 
budget, education, environmental regulation, workers' compensation, 
health care, and welfare reform.  Golden State Center policy briefings 
have become an important resource for reform-minded state legislators.

<h4>The Salvatori Center for the American Constitution</h4>

The Salvatori Center conducts academic programs that educate high 
school teachers and journalists in the principles of American Democracy.  
The work of the Center is to combat the disastrous trend toward 
multi-culturalism and anti-Americanism and to instill in teachers a deep 
understanding of the American founding.  The Center's publications have 
received national media attention.

<h4>The Asian Studies Center</h4>

The Asian Studies Center holds conferences and publishes books and 
essays on Pacific Rim issues.  Its work has been instrumental in promoting 
a greater understanding of the economic and strategic importance of the 
Far East.  The center has published on a number of issues including trade 
relations, Chinese reunification, defense burden sharing and the future of the 
pro-democracy movement in Communist China. 

<h4>The Center for the Study of the Natural Law</h4>

The Center for the Study of the Natural Law publishes books and essays 
on the state of family life in America.  Its work is directed at national and 
state policy makers to draw attention to the disastrous decline in morality 
that follows from failed social policies.  Recent publications include: On the 
Front Lines of the Culture War: Recent Attacks on the Boy Scouts of America 
and Moral Ideas for America.

<P>

<a name = "membership">

<hr size=4 noshade>

<center>

   <h1>Membership in The Claremont Institute</h1>

</center>

<hr size=4 noshade>

<P>

The Claremont Institute is a non-profit organization that relies on the 
support of individual donors to continue its work.  The Institute is a 
501(c)(3) tax-exempt organization and donations to the Institute are 
tax-deductible.  There are four different levels of membership:

<H3>Presidents Club</H3>

The Presidents Club was formed to involve businessmen and entrepreneurs 
directly in the work of the Claremont Institute, which consists largely of 
promoting the principles of limited government and free enterprise in 
Sacramento, Washington, D.C., and throughout the nation.  Presidents Club 
members receive all Institute briefings and reports, invitations to private, 
bi-monthly strategy sessions with Institute scholars and guest speakers, and 
invitations to an annual policy conference and retreat with policy experts and 
leading public figures from California and Washington.  Membership: Annual gift of $1,000.

<H3>Churchill Club</H3>

Churchill Club members receive all Institute briefings and reports and 
invitations to private bi-monthly strategy sessions with Institute scholars 
and guest speakers.  Membership: Annual gift of $500.

<H3>Patriots Club</H3>

Patriots Club members receive the Claremont Institute newsletter, The 
Public View, as well as selected Institute briefings and invitations to 
Institute special events.  Membership: Annual gift of $100.

<h3>General Membership</h3>

General members receive the Claremont Institute newsletter, The 
Public View, and announcements of publications and events.  
Membership: Annual gift of $25.
<P>

<a name = "remark">

<hr size=4 noshade>

<center>

   <h1>A few Remarks about The Claremont Institute and its Work</h1>

</center>

<hr size=4 noshade>

<P>

<B>

   "Where do we look for innovative, free market solutions to the problems 
   that confront California and our nation?  We turn to organizations like 
   the Claremont Institute, where some of America's top conservative 
   thinkers do their work."

</B>

<P>

--<B>Ronald Reagan</B>, 40th President of the United States

<P>

<hr size=4 noshade>

<P>

<B>

   "Right now there are very few groups that are effective against the liberal 
   policies and special interests that are corrupting our system.  Fortunately, 
   the Claremont Institute is an exception.  That's why I have chosen to become 
   a part of their efforts."

</B>

<P>

--<B>Bruce Herschensohn</B>, Distinguished Fellow, The Claremont Institute

<P>

<hr size=4 noshade>

<P>

<B>

   "The Claremont Institute is leading the fight for property rights, and to reduce 
   onerous and destructive regulation on the business community."

</B>

<P>

--<B>Donald Moe</B>, Senior Vice President, The Santa Margarita 
Company; Board Member, The Claremont Institute

<P>

