<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>FREE Perspectives</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY TEXT="#006699" VLink= "#003366" Background = "backgrndstripthin.gif">

<IMG HSPACE=15 SRC = "Masthead3.gif" WIDTH=506 HEIGHT=220 ALT = "FREE 
Perspectives">

<IMG ALIGN="LEFT" SRC="/free/Images/0.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=1350>
<H3><FONT COLOR = "#003366">An introduction to the Fall 1996 issue of FREE 
Perspectives.</FONT></H3>
<HR ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH= 25%>
<BR>
<A HREF="ChairmansWelcomeX1.html"><img ALIGN="Left" Vspace=2 Hspace=5 WIDTH=35 HEIGHT=31 ALT="Read Article" SRC="Freebiebtn.gif"></A><BR>
<FONT SIZE = 5><B>Chairman's Welcome:  Managing the 
Commons</B></FONT><BR>
<HR ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH=10%>
<FONT SIZE=3><I><B>
John Baden, Ph.D. reviews the prevalence and problems of <BR>
common-pool resources in the environment. He concludes that <BR>
management institutions are critical to conserving resources.</I></B>
<BR >
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3 COLOR = "#003366"><B>
What is a commons?  Why is managing the commons such a 
problem?<BR>
What are effective approaches?  The Chairman's Welcome answers 
<BR>these questions and introduces the various works in this 
issue.</B>
</FONT COLOR>
<P>
<HR ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH= 25%>
<BR>
<A HREF= "TragedyCommons.html"><img ALIGN="Left" Vspace=2 Hspace=5 WIDTH=35 HEIGHT=31 ALT="Read Article" SRC="Freebiebtn.gif"></A> 
<BR><FONT SIZE = 5><B>Tragedy of the Commons</B></FONT><BR>
<HR ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH= 10%>
<FONT SIZE=3><I><B>A reprint of Garrett Hardin's classic piece.<BR>
Garrett Hardin outlines his seminal work on the tragedy of 
<BR>the commons, where freedom in the commons brings ruin 
<BR>to all and the only solution is "mutual coercion, mutually agreed upon."</B></I></FONT>
<P>
<FONT  COLOR = "#003366"><B>
 Why are global fisheries drastically depleted?  Why is controlling 
<BR>greenhouse gases such a problem? Ever wonder why city parks 
<BR>and community resources get run down so easily, while nearly 
<BR>everyone maintains their home like it was their castle?  
<BR> Hardin's seminal essay, "The Tragedy of the Commons," 
<BR> answers these questions and more.</B></FONT COLOR>
<P>
<HR ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH= 25%>
<BR>
<A HREF ="EconomicsEcologyExchange.html"><img ALIGN="Left" Vspace=5 Hspace=5 WIDTH=35 HEIGHT=31 ALT="Read Article" SRC="Freebiebtn.gif"></A> 
<FONT SIZE = 5><B>Economics, Ecology, and Exchange:<BR> Free Market Environmentalism<BR></B></FONT>
<HR ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH= 10%>
<FONT SIZE=3><I><B>An excellent primer on the nature of different 
<BR>property types, and their effect on conservation. Robert Taylor
<BR> provides an excellent taxonomy of markets, resources, 
<BR>and property -- in the context of real-world environmental 
problems.</B></I></FONT>
<P>
<FONT =3 COLOR = "#003366"><B>
What is the difference between a commons and a private good? 
<BR> How are state goods different than collective goods?  How do
<BR>  different property systems affect resource conservation?  
<BR> Robert Taylor surveys the literature and real-world answers 
<BR> to these important questions. </B></FONT COLOR>
<P>
<HR ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH= 25%>
<BR>
<A HREF= "ConservationPerformance.html"><img ALIGN="Left" Vspace=2 Hspace=5 WIDTH=35 HEIGHT=31 ALT="Read Article" SRC="Freebiebtn.gif"></A> <BR>
<FONT SIZE = 5><B>Conservation Performance Under "Public" Tenure</B></FONT><BR>
<HR ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH=10%>
<FONT SIZE=3><I><B>National control of natural resources undermines 
the <BR>conservation ethic and promotes "tragedy of the commons" 
conditions.</B></I></FONT>
<P>
<FONT =3 COLOR = "#003366"><B>How well do communities conserve 
resources?  
<BR>Does state-run conservation programs perform better?  
<BR>How does government intrusion change the incentives and 
<BR>stewardship practices?  Owen Lynch and Janis Alcorn answer  
<BR>these questions from an international perspective.</B></FONT>
<P>
<HR ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH= 25%>
<BR>
<A HREF= "ViewfromAirlie.html"><img ALIGN="Left" Vspace=2 Hspace=5 WIDTH=35 HEIGHT=31 ALT="Read Article" SRC="Freebiebtn.gif"></A> <BR>
<FONT SIZE = 5><B>View from Airlie </B></FONT><BR>
<HR ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH= 10%>
<FONT SIZE=3><I><B>How we manage our natural resource is critical 
for their survival. 
<BR> This View from Airlie excerpt, also from a Claiborne-Ortenberg 
<BR> program, examines the role of institutions, authority, 
<BR> responsibility, and community in managing commons.</B></I>
<P>
<HR ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH= 25%>
<BR>

<A HREF= "NationalisationofLand.html"><img ALIGN="Left" Vspace=2 Hspace=5 WIDTH=35 HEIGHT=31 ALT="Read Article" SRC="Freebiebtn.gif"></A> <BR>
<FONT SIZE = 5><B>The Nationalisation of Land</B></FONT><BR>
<HR ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH= 10%>
<FONT SIZE=3><I><B>Nationalizing resources invites the tragedy, rather 
<BR>than promoting conservation as private ownership 
does.</B></I></FONT>

<P>
<FONT =3 COLOR = "#003366"><B>
What is the result of the collectivization of land?  Is the newly 
<BR>formed commons preserved or squandered?  Matt Ridley 
<BR>describes this loss of accountability under common 
<BR>ownership in England.</B></FONT>
<P>
<HR ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH= 25%>
<BR>
<A HREF= "CostsofInnovation.html"><img ALIGN="Left" Vspace=2 Hspace=5 WIDTH=35 HEIGHT=31 ALT="Read Article" SRC="Freebiebtn.gif"></A>
<BR> <FONT SIZE = 5><B>Costs of Innovation in the Commons</B></FONT><BR>
<HR ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH= 10%>
<FONT SIZE=3><I><B>Douglas Noonan describes how entrepreneurs, in their unending quest to create <BR>
value, can often be the cause tragedy in the commons.  He reminds us that<BR>
 entrepreneurs hold the key to solving the tragedy as well.</B></I></FONT>
<P>
<FONT =3 COLOR = "#003366"><B>What are the preconditions for the tragedy of the commons?  What is the 
<BR>role of the entrepreneur in the tragedy?  Doug Noonan demonstrates<BR> how entrepreneurial innovation both 
creates the valuable resources and <BR>the ensuing tragedy, and hints that such innovation should be guided <BR>towards creating valuable management solutions to commons problems.</B></FONT>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A HREF="/free/"><img WIDTH=260 HEIGHT=50 ALT="Home" SRC="/free/Images/Homebtn.gif"></A>
<p>
<HR>
