<DD><B>From the right:</B>
<BR>
<DD><I>Gene Randall to New York Governor George Pataki:</I> "Governor, the focus tonight of course is on
the keynote speech and that is by Representative Molinari who it's well known favors abortion
rights. Do you sense a dissatisfaction on this floor that she will be giving this address?"
<BR>
<DD><B>From the left:</B>
<BR>
<DD><I>Tom Brokaw to rape victim Jan Licence, who gave speech about victims' rights, 8/13:</I> "Do you
think -- this is a party that is dominated by men and this convention is dominated by men as
well, and I don't mean that in a pejorative sense. I mean it's just an objective reality here.
Do you think before tonight they thought very much about what happens in America with rape,
which is a terrible epidemic that we're suffering in this country?"
<BR>
<DD><I>Maria Shriver to a delegate, 8/13:</I> "Many moderate Republican women are actually considering
voting for the Democratic ticket because they look at this platform, they look at this party,
and they don't see anything they can embrace. Why should you tell them to stay?"
<BR>
<DD><I>Lisa Myers to Senator Olympia Snowe, 8/13:</I> "There are those who talk about their party believing
in tolerance and diversity, yet that in the reality the policies just don't reflect that, what's
your quick response?"
<BR>
<DD><B>From the left:</B>
<BR>
<DD><I>Maria Shriver to Jan Licence, rape victim, after her speech on victim's rights, 8/13:</I> "But why
[speak out] at a Republican convention? So many people have said that they don't think this
ticket, or perhaps this party, is supportive of women's issues. Why make this stand here?"
<BR>
<DD><I>Margaret Warner to U.S. Rep. John Boehner, 8/13:</I> "But do you think this convention in part has
been designed and stage managed as we're seeing, to soften the ideological edge that many voters
thought was either, too harsh about the Republican Congress?"
<BR>
<DD><I>Tom Brokaw to Virginia Governor George Allen, 8/13:</I> "Governor, are you not at all concerned
about what happens to the federal deficit, which is a major, major concern for most of the
delegates at this convention, based on the polling that we've done, if Bob Dole is able to put
into effect his 15 percent tax cut?"
<BR>
<DD><I>Brokaw to Allen:</I> "But if you say to your constituents in the state of Virginia, ` Listen, we're
going to cut it by 15 percent, taxes, but I can't touch 60 percent of the budget that we're
dealing with here,' and that's the reality that's facing Bob Dole because of Medicare and
defense spending and other things, do you think that we can get home-free here in seven years
and balance the budget?"
<BR>
<BR>
<a name="dem questions">
<DD><FONT  SIZE=+1><B>Democratic convention questions</B></FONT>
<BR>
<DD><B>From the left:</B>
<BR>
<DD><I>Jeff Greenfield, interviewing Representative Charles Rangel, 8/26:</I> "Charles Rangel of New York
will be the Chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee should the Democrats retake the
Congress. Congressman, it used to be said that when the Democrats make a firing squad they form
a circle, they love to rebel against an incumbent President, and you have the welfare bill and
the move to the center. You're from one of the most liberal cities in the country, why is the
dog not barking in the night? Why are you staying with the President given that discontent?"
<BR>
<DD><I>Michel McQueen interviewing Lynn Cutler, 8/26:</I> "I'm here with Lynn Cutler, whom many people who
follow in politics probably remember as the former vice chairman of the Democratic National
Committee from Iowa. She told me earlier when I was asking about concerns the President has
abandoned the liberal wing of the party that she is comparing her candidate not to perfection
but to Bob Dole. Isn't that right, Lynn, do the liberals in the party as you unashamedly
describe yourself feel abandoned by the President this year?"
<BR>
<DD><B>From the right: </B>
<BR>
<DD><I>Peter Jennings to Senator Christopher Dodd, 8/26:</I> "Lesson learned clearly in San Diego. When you
yourself were at the Republican Convention you accused that party of not being representative of
the mainstream of Republicans in the country. You're not much mainstream here either, are
you?"
<BR>
<DD><B>From the left:</B>
<BR>
<DD><I>Ed Bradley to Tom Hayden, 8/26:</I> "Senator Hayden, there are people who say the Democratic party
has become very pragmatic in an effort to win this election, they've given up their principles.
Your response to that?"
<BR>
<DD><I>Rita Braver to Geraldine Ferraro, 8/27:</I> "That's right, Dan, and there have been times that you
could actually feel the floor shaking with all the cheering here [in response to Hillary
Clinton's speech]. Mrs. Ferraro, why was there such a huge reception for the first lady? Is it
because she's been such an object of attack?"
<BR>
<DD><I>Ed Bradley to U.S. Rep. John Lewis, 8/27:</I> "Do you think it's going to be difficult [to mobilize
Democrats] given the positions he's taken, particularly on welfare, to get some people out?"
<BR>
<DD><I>Rita Braver to a Minnesota delegate, 8/28:</I> "Now that you've had some time to be here at the
convention, have your reservations gone away? How'd this speech cut through to you? You've been
worried about welfare."
<BR>
<DD><I>Ed Bradley to U.S. Rep. Ron Dellums, 8/29:</I> "Congressman Dellums was unhappy when the President
signed the welfare bill. I know you saw it not as welfare reform but more as a budget cut. What
does he have to do to fix it?"
<BR>
<DD><I>Bradley to Dellums:</I> "When the President is expected to say tonight that he's going to propose a
$3.5 billion jobs program for welfare recipients, is that enough?" 
<BR>
<DD><B>From the left:</B>
<BR>
<DD><I>Wolf Blitzer to Hillary Clinton, 8/27:</I> "What goes through your mind when you hear some of these
bitter attacks against you?"
<BR>
<DD><I>Bernard Shaw to Senator Bob Kerrey, 8/25:</I> "How can you do that when the leader of your party has
vetoed a welfare bill that many people in this hall feel he should have signed? I mean signed
which he should have vetoed. But politically he had no recourse."
<BR>
<DD><I>Wolf Blitzer to Mario Cuomo, 8/27:</I> "But on this issue of welfare reform which maybe, even if
Bill Clinton is reelected over eight years the most significant decision he makes. He signs this
welfare reform legislation into law. Could have this enormous, from your perspective, negative
impact on a million children could go into poverty. How do you rationalize that kind of decision
and now come forward and give this rousing endorsement for Bill Clinton to be reelected?"
<BR>
<DD><B>From the right: </B>
<BR>
<DD><I>Candy Crowley to a delegate, 8/28:</I> "Do you think that the teacher's unions have done enough to
change schools?  What I'm wondering is, the point from the Republicans is that the schools, most
everyone agreed, need help. Why not get some parent involvement in there through school
vouchers? Let people pick schools. Are you against that idea?"
<BR>
<DD><I>Wolf Blitzer to AFL-CIO chief John Sweeney, 8/28:</I> "Many of your members are Republicans. How do
you explain to them that you're using, in effect, their dues to help elect Democrats?"
<BR>
<DD><B>From the left:</B>
<BR>
<DD><I>Tom Brokaw to former Texas Governor Ann Richards, 8/27:</I> "You paid the price to some degree. You
lost the governership of Texas because this country still is a little bit schizoid, isn't it,
about the role of women in American politics?" 
<BR>
<DD><I>Maria Shriver to Hillary Clinton after her speech, 8/27:</I> "You are credited with really
redefining the role of First Lady and for doing that you've taken a lot of heat, a lot of
criticism. As you look back, do you wish you'd redefined it a little less?"
<BR>
<DD><I>Shriver:</I> "You talked a lot tonight about It Takes A Village, your book. And as you well know,
that was a lightning rod for criticism at the Republican convention. Kay Bailey Hutchison took
off on it, Bob Dole took off on it. How did that affect you when you heard about that?"
<BR>
<DD><B>From the Right:</B>
<BR>
<DD><I>David Bloom to James Carville about Hillary Clinton's speech, 8/27:</I> "I was struck by the fact
that she talked about health care and the need for more health care insurance for the
unemployed. That's a topic that got her and Bill Clinton into a lot of trouble two years ago.
Why would she revisit that tonight?"
<BR>
<DD><B>From the left:</B>
<BR>
<DD><I>Elizabeth Farnsworth to White House Deputy Chief of Staff Harold Ickes, 8/26:</I> "We're looking
tonight at this whole question of who the Democrats are. Did the President turn his back on
fundamental Democratic principles when he signed the welfare bill?"
<BR>
<DD><I>Farnsworth to Ickes:</I> "Does it worry you that the welfare, signing the welfare bill is unraveling
the safety net that took so long to put together?" Tom Brokaw to HHS Secretary Donna Shalala,
8/26: "If you were a poor single mother in a poor rural state in America, without many
resources, and you wanted to go to work, you want to do all the right things, but there aren't
many jobs for people who have real skills, wouldn't you be slightly terrified looking into the
next two years?"
<BR>
<DD><I>Maria Shriver to Georgia Governor Zell Miller, 8/27:</I> "We were just hearing Tim Russert talk
about the platform. A lot of the delegates here don't feel that the platform reflects the
Democratic Party that they joined five, ten years ago. Why are they wrong?"
<BR>
<DD><I>Shriver:</I> "But how concerned are you about the divisions, that people would say tension, this
isn't reflective, the Democratic Party sold out, it's a, it's a Republican Party with a
different name?"
<BR>
<DD><I>Shriver:</I> "But when you get out and you walk this floor of this convention center, do people come
up to you and say, `I am really angry about welfare reform, this is not what the Democratic
Party is about.'"
<BR>
<DD><B>From the right:</B>
<BR>
<DD><I>Lisa Myers to Senator John Breaux, 8/28:</I> "Doesn't that [Clinton moving to center] reinforce
claims of the President's critics who say that he is a man without many deep convictions, who in
fact is guided by the need to be liked, and by a burning desire to get re-elected?"
<BR>
<P>
<P>
<br>
<br>
<P>
<H5>
<CENTER> 
--L. Brent Bozell III;  <B>Publisher</B><br>
--Brent H. Baker, Tim Graham; <b>Editors</b><BR>
-- Geoffrey Dickens, Gene Eliasen, Jim Forbes, Steve Kaminski, <br> and
Clay Waters; <B>Media Analysts</B>,<BR>
-- Peter Reichel;<B> Circulation Manager</B>; 
<br>--Jessica Anderson, Matthew Turosz; <B>Interns</B><BR>
</H5>
</CENTER>
