<DOCNO>WT16-B28-89</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA022-000232-B031-269</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.savers.org:80/nationalreview/clinton/real.html 204.71.237.73 19970107231246 text/html 5732
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Tuesday, 07-Jan-97 23:12:55 GMT
Last-modified: Monday, 25-Nov-96 22:11:35 GMT
Content-length: 5548
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<BODY bgcolor="#fffff" LINK="red" VLINK="black">
<TITLE>The Real Clinton</TITLE>
<CENTER><img src="/nationalreview/images/real2.gif" ALT="The Real Clinton"></center>
<P>
<hr width=50%>
<P>
<!---------------------------------------------------------------->
The Real Clinton is more or less the opposite of the Real McCoy. What you see is very definitely not what you get, and indeed it may not be what you see a moment or two later. There is a chameleon quality about the 42nd President of the United States, a quicksilver opportunism, that enables him to don and doff identities like cloaks: the New Democrat who promises to end welfare as we know it, the paleo-liberal who takes on the Klan in defense of black churches, the economic statesman who steers by the bond market, the policy wonk avid to socialize one-seventh of the U.S. economy, the moralist who crusades against illegitimacy, the redneck roue with Astroturf in the back of his pick-up, the nostalgia-merchant who wants teenagers home by seven, the futurist with visions of an information superhighway, and at all times and on all occasions the bringer of empathy who feels the pain of that day's audience, whether millionaires or the poor, feminists or Good Ol' Boys, labor unions or blue-chip managements.
<P>
Underneath all the empathy, however, there is a set of policies and attitudes that gives a sort of consistency to his Administration, and even to his personality. In the following pages, we examine this Real Clinton from several angles. We look at Clintonism, that ambidexterity of campaigning right and governing left; at Clinton's steering of the economy by the stars of focus group and polling data; at the multicultural refashioning of the American identity in which he nervously colludes; at his stumblings down the multilateral by-ways of foreign policy, talking loudly and carrying a small stick; at his high-minded healing and sly exploitation of America's most entrenched problem -- race; at the manifold ways in which he, Hillary, and their confederates hidden in the last agencies of the alphabet, have abused federal power to extend their own personal power; and, finally, at that most extraordinary amphibian, Clinton the Bully Pulpiteer. Tales, in short, to / <I>``harrow up thy soul, freeze thy young blood</I> / <I>make thy two eyes, like stars, start from their spheres</I> / <I>thy knotted and combined locks to part / and each particular hair to stand an end</I> / <I>like quills upon the fretful porpentine.''</I> Now read on.
<P>

<P>

In our account of the Clinton years, <a href="/nationalreview/clinton/ramesh.html">Ramesh Ponnuru</a> looks at the political stratagems of the Potemkin Presidency, <a href="/nationalreview/clinton/rector.html">Robert Rector</a> recalls endless vacillations in welfare policy, <a href="/nationalreview/clinton/grace.html">Grace-Marie Arnett</a> gives socialized medicine an overdose, <a href="/nationalreview/clinton/kopel.html">David Kopel</a> wonders whether the Administration's crime policy will pay, <a href="/nationalreview/clinton/east.html">Terry Eastland</a> says that Clinton has the race card in trumps, <a href="/nationalreview/clinton/therns.html">Abigail Thernstrom</a> explains how the Justice Department is overruling the Supreme Court, <a href="/nationalreview/clinton/fonte.html">John Fonte</a> asks why the melting pot is on the back burner, <a href="/nationalreview/clinton/balint.html">Balint Vazsonyi</a> remembers America to Bob Dole,
<a href="/nationalreview/clinton/jenks.html">Rosemary Jenks</a> accuses Clinton of dual citizenship on immigration, Joshua Muravchik reminds Clinton that the world is a dangerous place, <a href="/nationalreview/clinton/samuel.html">Peter Samuel</a> gores the Administration's environmental fundamentalism, 
<a href="/nationalreview/clinton/reynolds.html">Alan Reynolds</a> weighs the harvest from the seven lean years, <a href="/nationalreview/clinton/bartlett.html">Bruce Bartlett</a> explains why the poor aren't getting richer, <a href="/nationalreview/clinton/niskan.html">William Niskanen</a> looks at worker productivity, Lawrence Kudlow wants to cut the growth deficit, <a href="/nationalreview/clinton/moore.html">Stephen Moore</a> has no deficit delusions, <a href="/nationalreview/clinton/mitchell.html">Daniel Mitchell</a> spikes tax hikes, Thomas Hopkins calculates the cost of re-regulation, <a href="/nationalreview/clinton/kate.html">Kate O'Beirne</a> contemplates Commissar Hillary, <a href="/nationalreview/clinton/rich.html">Rich Lowry</a> shows the devil is in the details, Christina Hoff Sommers finds feminists on the loose, James Bovard tells HUD to go home, <a href="/nationalreview/clinton/dealey.html">Samuel Dealey</a> discovers discrimination there, <a href="/nationalreview/clinton/arkes.html">Hadley Arkes</a> walks out on Clinton's sermonizing, <a href="/nationalreview/clinton/isaac.html">Rael Jean Isaac</a> catches Justice cutting deals with mobsters, and <a href="/nationalreview/clinton/levin.html">Mark R. Levin</a> catalogues the Clinton scandals. 
