<TITLE>NR Soapbox-weekday</TITLE>


<CENTER><img src="/nationalreview/images/soap2.gif" ALT="NR Soapbox"></center>.

<P>
<!---------------------------------------------------------------->
<blockquote>

The NR Soapbox is a place where <I>NR Online</I> readers can voice their opinions regarding the major issues of the day. Respond to the question directly, or comment on previous responses. Please keep comments brief (100 words or fewer). The featured question will change at the end of each week; comments will be updated daily.</blockquote>
<P>
<center>This week's question is:</center>
<center><H1><I>Should Congress Put A Rein on the Courts?</I></H1></center>


<br>
<center>To submit your comments,</center><br>
<center><A HREF="mailto:nronline@ix.netcom.com"><img src="/nationalreview/images/click2.gif" ALT="Click Here"></a>.<br></center>
<P>
Updated  1/6/97 (Well, not quite. See below.)
<HR>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------------------->

<P>
<b>AN APOLOGY: We are having problems gaining access to responses to this week's Soapbox question. We have just moved our offices, and are in the process of dealing with numerous communications snafus. We <I>will</I> post your submissions just as soon as our local phone company figures out how to fix our problems. Please continue to check in with us on daily basis, as we may have a handle on this as early as tommorrow (<I>HA!</I>). Please bear with us as we try to straighten this out. Thank you for being patient.</b>
<P>

<hr>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------>
1/2/97<br>
Congress overseeing the courts!—This might be the most frightening thought I've ever had. The Constitution provides for Judicial Review whereby the Supreme Court determines the constitutionality of law. The courts were established to de-politicize the law. We are now considering turning this on its head? Would Dick Gephardt find that <I>Roe</I> v. <I>Wade</I> was a clear instance of the Court making law rather than interpreting it? Would Newt Gingrich find that 209 is unconstitutional (a point with which I disagree)? No . . . they are partisan. Congress was given the power to confirm or reject any nominee. Perhaps if they took that responsibility more seriously, most questions of the court's integrity would simply disappear.<br>
<I>—breiferson@bloomaddept.com</I>
<hr>
<P>
1/2/97<br>
Yes, Congress should make laws that regulate the courts, but not in a way that compromises the separation of powers, and certainly not based on politics or public opinion. Rather, the law should mandate that the Bench include a significant number of non-attorneys. There is utterly no reason that lawyers should run all three branches of government, in addition to business, politics and especially legal education.<br>
<I>—j chanse, law student</I>
<hr>
<P>
1/2/97<br>
Yes. It's still "We the people . . ."; not, "I the judge . . ."<br>
<I>—Martin Registrada, Beaumont, Texas, registrada@aol.com</I>
<hr>
<P>
1/2/97<br>

Yes, congress should have the power to override a court decision. The Supreme Court is the most powerful branch in our government. Congress should exercise their rights using the elastic clause. Congress should be able to overturn ludicrous decisions that undermine the values of America. Decisions in cases such as Roe vs. Wade and those taking the Ten Commandments and prayer out of schools should be reviewed by Congress and if found necessary "veto" the Court's decision.<br>
<I>—Andrew C.Pearson Jr.</I>

<hr>
<P>
1/2/97<br>
Given the philosophy of your motley crew, I suggest you skip this step to curb the power of our courts, which have apparently functioned fairly well for over two hundred years, and just do away with them altogether. Then I would put Strom Thurmond in the White House so we could wave the Klan flag over the White House.<br>
<I>—Mario H. de la Plata, delaplat@ix.netcom.com</I>
<hr>
<P>
1/2/97<br>

Heck yes . . . the liberal wacko judges should be impeached!!!!!<br>
<I>—Duglywugly@aol.com</I>

<hr>
<P>
1/2/97<br>
Yes, Congress should make an attempt to control the courts. But long before that, journalism should do the job, by exposing these closet tyrants and all their works and pomps. Some way should be found to make public the records of each judge, and the light of public opinion should be made to shine on each of them.<br>
<I>—Patricia Sharp, PATSHARP-SANDIEGO@worldnet.att.net</I>

<hr>
<P>
1/2/97<br>
Victoria Carter, you got it right-on; there is no hope within the judicial labyrinth. However, your straight jacket idea just might be obtainable. Remember, this whole problem revolves around money. Remove the bucks, and you mitigate the problem. How about this? (1) Eliminate payroll-deduction of taxes; let the earners manage their own money. (2) Establish a uniform flat tax system, Dick Armey feels 17% will do. (3) Each month the wage earner would subtract one twelfth of his personal exemption from what he has made that month, then send a check for 17% of it. (4) Start teaching basic economics in the first grade. When the taxpayer sees his hard earned money being used as pork-barrel spending buy votes for politicians, it won't take long for both the courts and the government to change.<br> 
<I>—Bob Doran, dbredbob@cctrap.com</I>

<hr>
<P>
1/2/97<br>
When a student can finish law school without even reading the Constitution, we will be hard pressed to find judges who cherish and uphold the fundamental principles that have made America great. Should Congress put a reign on Congress? You are putting the cart ahead of the horse. First we must elect a Congress with the guts to stand up for what is just and right instead of what is politically correct or socially popular. We must do away with all the special group rights and return to the concept that the most important and inalienable rights are those of the individual, no matter what his color, creed, or religion.<br> 
<I>—B. E. Mossman, mossman@olypen.com</I>
<hr>
<P>
1/2/97<br>

Perhaps Congress should require that the Supreme Court enforce the Constitution rather than reinterpret it.<br>
—Fr. Steven J. Kelly, SSC, St. Mary's Episcopal Church, Charleroi, Pennsylvania, <I>kelfam@sgi.net</I>

<hr>
<P>
1/2/97<br>
Yes. The Courts are taking unto themselves powers which are not theirs under the Constitution. Moreover, they are claiming the exclusive power to determine whether or not their actions are proper and constitutional. The answer is a constitutional amendment, which it is unlikely that the congress will find the will and the gumption to institute. An equally grave issue is that, with the proliferation of case law and the extension of the courts into every area of our once private lives, the practitioners of the law, the attorneys, no longer can predict with any confidence what will be the consequences of any given motion or action. We now have the legal system as glorified slot machine, in which one puts in one's money and pulls the lever. Finally, even the randomly dispensed justice which our system affords, is beyond the economic reach of the average party. Thus we have a legal system available only to the wealthy, to which class we must strive to attain in self-defense, to the protected classes, for whom the government checkbook is opened, and to those attorneys, who are allowed to pull the lever of the slot machine without putting in their nickel.<br>
<I>—Eric L. Cox, capterk@ix.netcom.com</I>
<hr>
<P>
1/2/97<br>

I have watched our court system in action as it ruled again to save Californians from there evil selves! Again the courts ruled to trash the second state proposition that would have changed the course of not only California, but the whole Country! We must change our courts now and return to the Great land that our Forefathers bleed for. God bless America.<br> 
<I>—SupperDoo@aol.com</I>
<hr>
<P>
1/2/97<br>

I think it is clear that the judicial system has long ago ceased to serve free America. The judicial system of the United States exists today to benefit one group and one group only, and that is attorneys. We would be far better served by a non-antagonistic, interrogatory form of judiciary modeled perhaps on that of Germany. We have made the existing jury system a sacred cow, and as with most sacred cows, we're not sure precisely why we're not killing them instead of feeding them, but we're sure that our forefathers who told us to do so must have known. It is time to re-examine this system in the cold light of logic and reason, not sentiment. Changes must be made. As for as the interpretative function of the courts, it does serve as an ingenious form of checks and balances that probably should not be tampered with. An extremely pragmatic understanding of human nature and group dynamics led our forefathers to include this as a safeguard against "mobocracy." Their other safeguard, the appointing of senators as opposed to the election of same, has already been obviated. A nation full of people who will pay $7200 for a Tickle-Me Elmo doll that will be $32 on the shelves shortly is not rational enough to live without a strong Supreme Court.<br> 
<I>—Laura Patterson</I>
<hr>
<P>
1/2/97<br>

I find it terribly amusing that a liberal like Leslie would feel that "an activist judiciary is crucial to a functioning democracy"—no, little girl, an activist judiciary is only crucial to a government that does things the way YOU want them to without having to bother with other people's opinions, feelings, OR rights. Conservatives may cry out for the Judiciary to enforce the 2nd amendment, but only because it is ripe hypocrisy to have an activist court that ONLY legislates from the bench in favor of liberal causes. No, Leslie, let's face it, you don't want democracy, you want a dictator—so long as she does it your way, and so
you can distort every opinion which doesn't agree with yours as oppressive and evil (which is what liberals always do when they don't want to have to think too hard about their own opinions).<br>
<I>—Dean Esmay, esmay@syndicomm.com</I>
<hr>
<P>
1/2/97<br>

Federal courts interfering with a state's internal matters is unconstitutional. Any ruling, such as in California's Prop. 209 is illegal and a smack in the face to all Americans in every state. Judicial activism is illegal—despite the threat of federal force. Americans have the moral and constitutional right to use whatever force necessary to repel and abolish the tyranny of judicial activism. But I sure hope Congress does something about it first.<br>
<I>—Asanti2@aol.com</I>
<hr>
<P>
1/2/97<br>

I think the courts have co-opted WAY too much power for themselves and are not answerable to the people. They legislate from the bench and that is a CLEAR violation of the constitution. The checks provided against them from the constitution are clear and so are their powers. THE COURTS HAVE SUPERSEDED THEM!! It is time for their power to be reigned in. Liberals allowed the powers of the court to expand to further the liberal agenda. Even though conservatism is taking over, we must not allow ourselves to fall into the judicial trap. We must go forward on legislative acts and ignore, as much as we can, the judicial corruption that has pervaded the judiciary (thanks to the liberals). Legislation IS the power of the people, not the judiciary, as the liberals believe. The judiciary has been used by the liberals to BYPASS the will of the people! Now everyone knows, the reason for the judiciary is to protect the people from the tyranny of the masses, but the people are much better educated today then 200 years ago. Also we have 200 years of experience behind us. WE KNOW WHAT WE ARE DOING!!!! End judiciary enslavement now!!!!!<br>
<I>—jc</I>
<hr>
<P>
1/2/97<br>

This is rather a moot question. The question might well have been "Should the People Put a Rein on Congress"? Congress is responsible for the making of laws consistent with and/or within the restrictions of the US Constitution. States rights are "not to be" impugned unless matters exceeding the rights of the State are in question. Lawmakers invariably test these premises and submit to the electorate a concoction of "favorable or popular" jurisprudence. This, with the knowledge that it will end in court. Changing a few judges will not change the situation. If true tests are applied through appeals and our learned judicial deems a contest of interpretation with the Constitution is in order; then and only then should the Supreme judicial powers come into arbitration. This tends to make the opposition to any Supreme decision decry political infatuation. I've lived through the depression and several wars, good times, hard times are always going to be around. We have a healthy political system and a very precise Constitution that needs no tinkering with. The best for all to do is fill our legislative and congressional domains with the most fervent of learned folks. We will continue to have detestable laws, politicians, and decisions—and on the other hand, many acceptable laws, politicians, and decisions. We are a nation of laws. This is life and a pretty darn good one at that.<br>
<I>—Arthur Stallwitz</I>
<hr>
<P>
1/2/97<br>

What would happen if the Supreme Court ruled on a 5-4 majority that law-abiding adults under 21 were ineligible to vote in federal elections? What would we do if Clinton and Gore were removed from office for obstruction of justice in the V. Foster affair, and tax fraud (with regard to Buddhist Temple donations to the DNC) respectfully, and the AFL-CIO brought suit to block Speaker Gingrich from becoming President, and the Supreme Court sided with the union? What would we do? The only true check on government power, of any kind, is a well-educated, mature, populace. It also helps if that populace is well armed. Watch for Amendment II, like Amendment X, to be declared unconstitutional.<br>
<I>—Matthew Wisbey, Kekaha, HI</I>
<hr>
<P>
1/2/97<br>

Permit the Supreme Court to invalidate or otherwise declare unconstitutional a state law ONLY by a UNANIMOUS decision of the court. This act would seriously check the Court's trampling of states' Rights. If unanimous jury verdicts are required for criminal trials, then protecting the will of the people, as expressed by their duly elected legislatures, deserves no less rigorous a procedure.<br>
<I>-?</I>
<hr>
<P>
1/2/97<br>

I don't know how, but the courts should be required to interpret and enforce the law. They should not be allowed to attempt "social engineering"{ or any other fad).<br>
<I>—aschmidt@sprynet.com</I>
<hr>
<P>
1/2/97<br>

As conservatives, we support the "original intent" interpretation of the Supreme Court. That is that this judicial body is, by definition, to review cases to determine constitutionality of rulings and decisions. This deliberating body was to be made up of the great judicial minds of the time. Can anyone detect where we might have some deviation yet?<br>
<I>—Frank E. McDonough, CSCFEM@ARCOCHEM.COM</I>
<hr>
<P>
1/2/97<br>

Congress and the Courts shouldn't be linked. They are to a certain extent, but this should be maintained as little as possible. The bigger question is whether the courts have a right to interfere with what has been passed down in an election. Example: the affirmative-action case in California. Does a federal judge have a right to block this action??? I always thought that the courts were there to see that laws were enforced . . . Could you help me??<br>
<I>—Rudy</I>
<hr>
<hr>
<P>

12/18/96<br>
Randy and others, It should be clear to you since the election that leaving pure politics in the hands of the electorate is a lost cause. Instant gratification is the rule of the land in their minds. Americans in general have their wants, their needs, and their rights muddled together. They think that if they want something bad enough it becomes a need. And if they can't get it, it becomes their right to have it. It seems the judiciary feeds on this and therefore the legislature is so busy trying to "fix" what the courts decree that they are unable to make reasonable law.<br> 
<I>—dmartin@vbe.com</I> 
<hr>
<P>
12/18/96<br>
This is an easy one. The courts are NOT allowed to hear cases involving the internal affairs of any state. Article III, Section 2, not to mention Amendment X of the US Constitution, spell out the scope of Judicial power. The courts may not hear cases involving the laws of a particular state, unless it is appealed as to an issue arising under the US Constitution. Most of the cases heard by the Court do not fall under its legal scope, and are therefore null and void. California Prop 187, 209, <I>Roe</I> v <I>Wade</I>, etc. are internal state affairs and out of the reach of the federal courts. Judges and Justices who do not respect their very limited scope should be removed for behavior inconsistent with their service. The US Constitution is a very precise and clear document; there are no "vapors," "emanations", or "penumbras" incorporated into its substance. Justices who have a difficult time with this concept should be promptly retired.<br>  
<I>—alohawz@aloha.net</I>
<hr>
<P>
12/18/96<br>

What Congress should do is actively review the decisions of courts such as the decision which occurred in California to block the popular implementation of Prop. 209 to end affirmative action. Congressional committees should be formed to look into controversial exercise of judicial power and decide if the federal judges making such decisions by their records merit impeachment. The indefinite terms of federal judges were meant to shield them from the influence of short-term political pressures, but liberal judges have regarded them as means to thwart the implementation of conservative legislation. Congress should simply exercise their powers to protect the rights of citizens in the practice of democracy.<br>  
<I>—Dan Shaw, dshaw@nbserv2.dseg.ti.com</I>

<hr>
<P>
12/18/96<br>
The real question is: Who runs this country? The people or an elite bunch of self-serving educrats who know what is best for each of us? Someday the people of this country might stand up for what is right!<br>  
<I>—Eric P. Thompson, ept51@ctainforms.com</I>
<hr>
<P>
12/18/96<br>

The Congress should put a rein on the courts, but it won't. As long as the Supreme Court keeps giving liberals the decisions they want, Democrats will block any efforts to restore power to the legislatures. Almost all the checks and balances on the courts require either two-thirds of Congress, or 60% of the Senate and presidential signature, neither of which Republicans are likely to have anytime soon. Senate Republicans could block Clinton's liberal appointments, but they are too gutless. Court reform is just not going to happen.<br>  
<I>—Russell Van Zandt, russvz@wwa.com</I>
<hr>
<P>
12/18/96<br>

If you think that control over the judicial system should be given to Congress, now that Congress is in conservative hands, remember what happened to Robert Bork when he sought confirmation. Remember what almost happened to Clarence Thomas. However, judges and the activist legislation they create must be brought under control, since they are now essentially unaccountable. There have been no checks on judges' activist liberalism, which is why we're in the trouble we're in today; the people themselves never voted for most of the liberal legislation that is destroying this country. However, the power to make judges accountable must not lie with Congress, since Congress itself was unaccountable for 40 years of nonstop liberal Democrat rule. There should be a safeguard within the system itself, a safeguard that is regulated by the Constitution. The only real safeguard would be a Constitutional amendment that Congress cannot touch, an amendment limiting the power of judges. This could take the form of term limits, recall, or legislation that requires strict construction of the Constitution in any judicial interpretation. Newt Gingrich often states that the Founding Fathers designed a system so inefficient that no dictator could force it to work. But unfortunately, it wasn't so inefficient that Congressional barons, imperial presidents, and judicial petty tyrants couldn't find loopholes. All of these branches, rather than acting as checks and balances on each other, have conspired to create dictatorial agencies that go unregulated, and legislation that is beyond the reach of the public. The key to getting this leviathan state under control is not to give any one branch special jurisdiction over another—such as Congressional control over the judiciary—but to put the entire system in a strait jacket. We must tie the entire system in so many knots that it will have to become responsive to the people that it is supposed to serve. This might take the form of limiting executive privilege and autonomy, enacting term limits on Congress, giving Congress control over Federal agencies, enacting a balanced budget amendment, and so on. The government should have unlimited authority to control itself while leaving us free. However, this may well be impossible, since the ability to tie the system in knots implies the existence of a degree of control that we no longer have, if we ever really had it at all. Ultimately, the ability to control the system lies with the people—and if the people remain ignorant, shallow, emotion-driven, dull-witted, and foolish in their condition of childlike dependence. We will all continue to live under the dictatorial control of the monster that we have created.<br>  
<I>—Victoria Carter, vcarter@zoo.uvm.edu</I>
<hr>
<P>
12/18/96<br>

Sir Winston Churchill stated, more than fifty years ago, "The women's suffrage movement is only the small edge of the wedge, if we allow women to vote it will mean the loss of social structure and the rise of every liberal cause under the sun." Now, some fifty years later, only Judge Robert Bork has had the courage to state, "Radical feminism is the most destructive and fanatical movement to come down to us from the Sixties. . . . Totalitarian in spirit, it is antagonistic to traditional Western culture and proposes the complete restructuring of society, morality, and human nature." And one of the major forces of that Radical Feminism, Catherine A. MacKinnon, has asserted that "feminism could supplant both Marxism and liberalism as a theory of politics." Should Congress put a rein on the courts? Indeed. But what is most needed is an emboldened male and female leadership that will have the courage of a Churchill and a Bork to tell the American public what it already knows, but quakes to acknowledge—End Feminism, restore America. The much derided, potatoe spelling champ Dan Quayle had a splendid moment when he challenged Murphy Brown, and that earned him years of scornful ridicule. Can it be possible that this mild-mannered ex-vice-president has evidenced more spine than the entire United States Congress?<br>  
<I>—Jerry Rowles, jrowle19@ecity.net</I>
<hr>
<P>
12/18/96<br>

Constitutionally, the courts only exist to interpret the law. The purpose of the federal courts and Supreme Court of the United States is only to decide the constitutionality of laws passed by the legislative body. In far too many instances, we find the court "creating law" by its ruling in issues. Precedents are set, and are interpreted as law by the populace. Technically, if a law is found to be unconstitutional, then it is up to the legislature to formulate a law that is constitutional regarding the issue at hand. Our nation has gone too long in permitting courts to "write law" by their rulings. Congress should place reins on the courts by re-writing laws that the court rules to be unconstitutional, especially when this is true on technical bases only. In addition, constitutionally, the Executive Branch of our government should only be the enforcer of laws passed by the legislature. It is Congress that represents the people—not the Courts, nor the President.<br>  
<I>—Henry in Waco, TX</I>
<hr>
<P>
12/18/96<br>

U. S. Constitution Article III, Section 2: "In all cases affecting ambassadors, other public ministers and consuls, and those in which a state shall be a party, the Supreme Court shall have original jurisdiction. In all the other cases before-mentioned, the Supreme Court shall have appellate jurisdiction, both as to law and fact, with such exceptions, and under such regulations as the Congress shall make." I would like to recommend for your reading the Anti-Federalist Papers. The Anti-Federalist were written at the time when the Constitution was being formulated and its adoption considered. It critiqued of the Constitution and said much about the Judicial branch, which has come true.<br>  
<I>—Jaime R. Purcell</I>

<hr>
<P>
12/18/96<br>
The primary purpose of the federal judiciary is to protect our individual freedoms, and the rights of the people and the states, against encroachment by an oppressive central government. Sadly, the judges don't seem to do a very good job of it, but this is not the fault of our constitutionally mandated tripartite system; it is because the executive branch appoints lemons. If something needs to be reformed, it is the bloated and unresponsive executive branch of the Federal Government. We could begin by electing ethical presidents.<br>  
<I>—Nick Chase, nick15@eve.assumption.edu</I>

<hr>
<P>
12/18/96<br>
Of course Congress should put a rein on the courts. Thomas "I love a good revolution" Jefferson put it well: "To consider judges as the ultimate arbiters of all constitutional questions [is] a very dangerous doctrine indeed, and one which would place us under the despotism of an oligarchy. Our judges are as honest as other men and not more so. They have, with others, the same passions for party, for power, and the privilege of their corps…[a]nd their power is all the more dangerous as they are in office for life and not responsible . . .  to the elective control."<br> 
<I>—Van Godbold, jericho@umich.edu</I> 
<hr>
<hr>
<P>

12/17/96<br>
The Courts absolutely must be given the message that they exist to carry out the laws of the land, in addition to throwing out those that violate the Constitutional rights of the people. The Courts DO NOT have the right to legislate through their judicial process. The role of Congress must be, collectively, individually, and through its Judiciary Committees, to ensure that all candidates for appointment are well grounded in the historical, Christian religious basis for their role. The basic foundations of right and wrong derive from our Founding Fathers' actions and words during the writing and adoption of the Declaration of Independence, and the Constitution. Members of Congress must recognize this, affirm it, and demonstrate it during their formal proceedings such as in the Senate's advise and consent function, or be candidates for ousting at the next election. American citizens must recognize their moral responsibility in this process, and not be duped by the liberal establishment including the teachers' unions, if the decaying process of this Republic is to be stopped!! The new Congress must be bold, and LEADERS must step forward with personal conviction!<br> 
<I>—Bill</I>
