<P>
12/17/96<br>

The American public is the only hope for reining in the federal court Frankenstein monster! Congress is basically useless in this day and age. The American people will, eventually, simply tell the courts to "go to hell" in the same manner as they did the "Dred-Scott" courts back in the 1800s. If the people do this via Congress, it will require a massive overthrow of both the Democrats and Republicans who have created the judicial beast through apathy and politics. We are currently being ruled by a 5–4 black-robed oligarchy that ignores traditional U.S. (not-multicultural) traditions and institutions. If not altered, the country is going to collapse in the not-so-distant future.<br> 
<I>—kackr@aol.com</I>
<hr>
<hr>
<P>

12/16/96<br>
The existence of an independent court, whether this was or was not intended by the Founding Fathers, is certainly a desirable check against the tyranny of the majority. The majority is not always right; Rousseau, not a favorite with conservatives (with good reason), nevertheless held correctly that the majority is right only when it is right! However, the federal court system has become an oligarchy run by liberals with the support of liberal law schools and bar associations. It is time not for the abolition of the autonomy of the court system but for its modification. We should give the Congress a greater role. Perhaps a 3/4 vote of both houses of Congress should override a court decision about the unconstitutionality of legislation in certain carefully controlled circumstances. Robert Bork, in his book <I>Slouching Towards Gomorrah</I>, has some good ideas about this.<br>
<I>—Norman Ravitch, norman.ravitch@ucr.edu</I>
<hr>
<P>
12/16/96<br>
The liberal courts' usurpation of citizens' freedoms is just another example of the slave-master mentality of the left. Clinton's claim of acting out of compassion does not make acceptable his rape of our rights. The Clinton courts have done more violence to our basic civil rights, as expressed in the Bill of Rights, than all of America's enemies throughout history.<br>
<I>—Ed Johnson, ej@unlinfo.unl.edu</I>

<hr>
<P>
12/16/96<br>
It is time that somebody or some entity do something about the courts. I am certain that when the Constitution was written, no one had any thought of the courts being stacked with socialist activists far more intent on furthering their own agenda than clearly interpreting the Constitution. In the recent California case concerning the CCRI, a U.S. District Judge, Thelton Henderson, literally extorted the case from the legally chosen judge, using as the reason an absolute and easily substituted lie. Judge Henderson and many other left-wing court appointees have track records of pure socialist-activist decisions where the Constitution is completely ignored. One begins to wonder if these decisions fall under the mandate of the Constitution which states, "The judges, both of supreme and inferior courts, shall hold their offices during good behavior." It would seem that completely ignoring the Constitution, in favor of your own political beliefs, would qualify as bad behavior. If Congress is the place, where are they when these blatant violations are routinely dismissed as normal procedure?<br> 
<I>—Bob Doran, dbredbob@cctrap.com</I>

<hr>
<P>
12/16/96<br>
Leave well enough alone. If our elected representatives did their jobs instead of punting whenever a difficult issue arises, reigning in the judiciary would not be an issue.<br> 
<I>—Michael J Karagozian, TD24112@link.com</I>

<hr>
<P>
12/16/96<br>
In the cases of 209, 187, welfare reform, yes, somehow we have to limit idiot judges in the Ninth District. Boy am I glad I moved from Taxifornia to South Dakota two years ago where unusual things are the Corn Palace and jackalopes at Wall Drug. I think I remember some folks leaving England for points west a while back over similar issues.<br> 
<I>—Ken Russell, The Arlington Pottery, gone2pot@iw.net</I>
<hr>
<P>
12/16/96<br>

The people can control the courts by controlling for whom they vote. When conservative thought controls legislative bodies, those nominated for appointed offices and judgeships tend to be of the same mindset. The liberals do the same. Wise and thinking citizens not only vote, but cast their ballots for right-thinking people of unquestioned morals, both professionally and personally. This is for any election, from President to dogcatcher.<br> 
<I>—Richard McKee, Dover, Delaware</I>
<hr>
<P>
12/16/96<br>

Yes Congress should rein in the Courts, although I am not sure how that would be accomplished. The Courts have too many times overturned the will of the people, and the will of the people reins supreme!<br> 
<I>—Paul Oksnee, poksnee@netscape.com</I>

<hr>
<P>
12/16/96<br>
The men who wrote the Constitution carefully designed a Federal Government with three separate and distinct parts, each part to act as a check against the other two. This implies an equal division of power among the three parts.<br> 
<I>—Carl Conner, cconner@grove.net</I>

<hr>
<P>
12/16/96<br>
Oh sure, reign in the courts now that they've passed a few decisions conservatives don't like. Last week, though, you were all just dying for an interventionist court to overturn the Brady Bill. Judges are committed to leaving their prejudices outside the courtroom, but nothing stops voters from carrying their bigotry into the voting booth. So Californians choose a strident repeal of the state's guarantee of civil rights, and Congress/puritanical legislatures forbid states from acknowledging the loving union of same-sex couples. The duty of the courts is to let democracy work, but keep it in check by screening out centuries-old hatreds (or sexist worldviews, such as those that deny women the right to control their own bodies). As such, an activist judiciary is crucial to a functioning democracy—unless, of course, you think women and minorities don't count.<br>
<I>—Leslie G. Burton</I>

<hr>
<P>
12/16/96<br>
Recent events suggest that the power is out of balance, having shifted toward the Judicial. This works to the advantage of the Executive which has the power of appointment. The legislative is weakened and with it the voice of the electorate. Two initiatives passed by the voters of California have been, in effect, nullified by federal judges. A majority of California's voters, its Governor and its legislature have been over ruled by one person who seemingly has the power of a dictator. At the very least the Congress should require that a federal judge explain in concrete rather than abstract 'read between the lines' detail exactly why he believes the law he over turned is unconstitutional. Lacking a rational reason, the judge should be overruled This last case is a real farce. The judge evidently believes that outlawing discrimination is unconstitutional! Great care must be taken to stop this type of nonsense without altering the system set up by the Founders. Restoration, not alteration, is what's needed here. I believe that we should not let Congress put a reign on the courts. The reason is simple . . . balance of power. Congress has a chance during a justice's appointment to approve a justice. Our Republican Congress should really scrutinize Clinton's appointments. Not just let them in without a hitch. Now it's too late to do anything. Maybe we should let the Citizens of the US put a reign on the courts? What do you think???<br> 
<I>—RandyA8878@aol.com</I>
<hr>
<hr>
<P>

