<IMG SRC="../images/nwe.redrule.gif" WIDTH=520 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0><BR><NOBR><font size=-1>Published in Washington, D.C.&#009;<B>January 12, 1997 -- Edition</B>&#009;<IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=0>"America's Newspaper"<BR></font></NOBR><A HREF="buttons.3.gif.map"><MAP NAME="clientmap0"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="436,1,519,18" HREF="../watch/watch.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="351,1,428,16" HREF="../letters/letters.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="263,0,345,19" HREF="exclusive.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="177,1,257,18" HREF="culture.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="90,0,172,19" HREF="#linkTOP"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="2,1,86,18" HREF="../index.html"></MAP><IMG SRC="images/buttons.3.gif" WIDTH=520 HEIGHT=19 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="Navigation Bar graphic, see text links below." border=0 USEMAP="#clientmap0" ISMAP></A><BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif"  ALIGN=top WIDTH=0 HEIGHT=8><BR><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=520><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN="3" ROWSPAN="5"><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=325><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1"><FONT SIZE=6>White House denies aides<BR>squeezed Asian-Americans<BR></FONT><ALIGN=Left><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=100% ALIGN=Center NOSHADE>ASSOCIATED PRESS<HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=100% ALIGN=Center NOSHADE><IMG SRC="../images/cap.T.gif" alt=T border=0 align=left height=34>he White House sharply disputed a report that a presidential aide helped devise a plan to raise millions of dollars from Asian-Americans for last year's campaign by offering rewards to the largest donors, including access to President Clinton. <BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>The New York Times reported Dec. 28 that Doris Matsui, a deputy assistant to the president, and John Huang, a former Democratic National Committee fund-raiser at the center of a scandal over improper and illegal campaign contributions, conceived the strategy, intended to raise $7 million from Asian-Americans.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>But Lanny Davis, a White House spokesman who handles damage control for the president, said Mrs. Matsui scrupulously avoided fund raising in her post as director of White House outreach to Asian-Americans.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Mrs. Matsui's activities have come under scrutiny because of a 33-page Democratic National Committee document released late last month by the White House. It outlined a plan by the DNC and the Clinton administration to improve ties to the Asian community - while at the same time raising millions of dollars from its members.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>"Mrs. Matsui has indicated that she was not involved in the development of the campaign plan," Mr. Davis said. "More importantly, Mrs. Matsui has not engaged in any solicitation of contributions or any other improper fund-raising activities."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>It is illegal for government employees to solicit political contributions.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>The unprecedented goal of raising the $7 million in funds was laid out in a "National Asian Pacific American Campaign Plan," which was part of 3,000 pages of the DNC's records made public over the last two weeks.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>The recently released records, mostly from the files of Mr. Huang, the DNC's chief fund-raiser among Asian-Americans, raise questions about whether White House officials illegally participated in fund-raising and campaign activities.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>In addition, the party's goal of raising the money may have helped create a high-pressure atmosphere that led to at least $1.2 million subsequently being returned to contributors as improper donations.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Under the plan's guidelines, invitations to the White House were extended to members of the Asian Pacific American Leadership Council, or to individuals giving at least $10,000 and companies at least $15,000 to the Democratic committee.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>The strategy was to "reward APALC members by inviting them to special White House or other events" with the president and to "solicit input," the records show.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Mr. Davis said Mrs. Matsui, wife of Rep. Robert T. Matsui, California Democrat, headed the Asian Pacific American Working Group while Mr. Huang was involved with the Asian Pacific American Leadership Council, a group of DNC-related contributors.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>A senior White House official, speaking on the condition of anonymity, said Mrs. Matsui does not recall having read the campaign plan. The official also said the document's author, DNC official William Kaneko, has told administration officials he is not certain whether the 33-page document was even forwarded to Mrs. Matsui's office.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>No evidence suggests that donors won changes in policy, even though White House meetings often featured discussions of Mr. Clinton's policies toward Asian nations, especially China.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>But in the past month, two connections between Clinton administration policy and the Lippo Group, an Asian company that paid Mr. Huang a $780,000 bonus just before he moved to the Commerce Department, have come under question.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Earlier last month, the president acknowledged that he received a letter in 1993 from Mochtar Riady - founder of the Indonesia-based conglomerate that donated hundreds of thousands of dollars to the Clinton campaign - seeking normalization of trade relations with Vietnam at a time when the company was moving its $6.9 billion real estate and investment empire into that country.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Mr. Clinton denied the letter influenced his decision to end a 30-year trade embargo on Vietnam, which he did in 1994.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Late last month, the Associated Press reported a connection between Lippo and Mr. Clinton's designation of 1.7 million acres of Utah wilderness - known as the Kaiparowits - as a national monument.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>A U.S. mining company owned by a British family was ready to tap a huge reserve of environment-friendly coal there but was forced to reverse course with Mr. Clinton's announcement in September. Lippo has business interests related to coal: One of its subsidiaries was involved in a now dormant joint venture to run a clean-coal-fueled power plant in China.</TD></TR></TABLE> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN=1 ROWSPAN=1><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=9><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top> <TD ALIGN=left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1"><IMG SRC="../images/vertical.gif" WIDTH=9 HEIGHT=60 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="" border=0></TD></TR></TABLE> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN=1 ROWSPAN=1><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=180><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top><TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN=1 ROWSPAN=1><A HREF="mailto:wtadvt@wt.infi.net"><IMG SRC="../ads/house_ad.180.gif" WIDTH=180 HEIGHT=60 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="TWT House Ad 1" border=0></A></TD></TD></TABLE></TD></TD></TABLE><center><p><a href="#linkTOP">Go back to the top of this article.</A></center></TD></TR>
