<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Washington Times-Culture Wars</TITLE></HEAD><BODY><P><!-- HTML Copyright (c) 1996 The Washington Times -->
<!-- Jamie White-->
<!-- webmastr@wt.infi.net -->
<A NAME="linkTOP"><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#ff0800"
VLINK="#6f6f6f" ALINK="#000000"></A>
<center><NOBR><IMG SRC="../images/twtbanner.gif" WIDTH=375 HEIGHT=42 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="The Washington Times" border=0>
<A HREF="../aboutNWE.html">
<IMG SRC="images/culturewars.gif" WIDTH=145 HEIGHT=42 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="Culture Wars" border=0></A>
</NOBR>
<IMG SRC="../images/nwe.redrule.gif" WIDTH=520 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0><BR><NOBR><font size=-1>Published in Washington, D.C.<IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=0>&#009;<B>January 12, 1997 -- Edition</B>&#009;<IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=0>"America's Newspaper"<BR></font></NOBR><A HREF="buttons.3.gif.map"><MAP NAME="clientmap2"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="436,1,519,18" HREF="../watch/watch.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="351,1,428,16" HREF="../letters/letters.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="263,0,345,19" HREF="exclusive.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="177,1,257,18" HREF="culture.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="90,0,172,19" HREF="#linkTOP"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="2,1,86,18" HREF="../index.html"></MAP><IMG SRC="images/buttons.3.gif" WIDTH=520 HEIGHT=19 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="Navigation Bar graphic, see text links below." border=0 USEMAP="#clientmap2" ISMAP></A><BR><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=520><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN="3" ROWSPAN="5"><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=325><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1"><FONT SIZE=6>Four Horsemen ditch steeds<BR>for exhibit's Trans Am<BR></FONT><ALIGN=Left><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=100% ALIGN=Center NOSHADE><ALIGN=Left>By <ALIGN=Left>Julia Duin<BR><font size=1>THE WASHINGTON TIMES<HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=100% ALIGN=Center NOSHADE></font><IMG SRC="../images/cap.T.gif" alt=T border=0 align=left height=34>he third millennium dawns in four years and when Canadian artist John Scott was pondering over how to portray it, he came up with a black Pontiac Trans Am. <BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Trans Ams are muscle cars, he thought -- the perfect vehicle to portray the Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse, the dreaded symbols in the Book of Revelation that kill off a quarter of the Earth's population.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Should that quartet appear today, he figured they would ditch horses as being too archaic and choose a more harrowing vehicle.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Moreover, this brutal-looking pit bull of a car was the perfect quasi-religious, semisatanic symbol for today's violent youth subculture.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>"I am sure," he says, "more people have gotten out of Trans Ams to do violence than any other car made. It is the most sinister car going."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Portrayed in images ranging from German Albrecht Durer's 15th-century woodcuts to anti-nuclear art of the 1960s, the specter of a coming millennium has fascinated Western civilization.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>The last two decades have reflected a rising American anxiety about the future, depicted in films such as "Road Warrior," "Escape From New York," "Escape From L.A." and "Blade Runner." Their story lines, set in bleak 21st century cities turned into police states or terrorized by gangs, do not show a Second Coming as much as they show a hell on Earth.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>The modern art world has dipped its collective toe slowly into visions of the morass. In "New Visions of the Apocalyptic," a 1988 exhibition at the Rhode Island School of Design, 19 artists displayed works on the defoliant Agent Orange and scenes from literal hells with titles such as "Figures With Bleeding Eyes."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>The one hopeful piece in the exhibit was artist Ruth Kligman's "Apocalyptic Art," an abstract rendering of color and light inspired by Revelation 22:5, which promises night will be vanquished forever and the redeemed "will not need the light of a lamp or the light of the sun, for the Lord God will give them light. And they will reign for ever and ever."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>The other depictions were secular ruins: the atom bomb, the Nazi Holocaust and ecological decay, as the plant world dies first when the world's end is imminent. Other scenes came from a world in which morality has faded, replaced by random, escalating violence from a new urban predator class of youths.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Although Mr. Scott, 46, does not call himself a Christian -- "I've been too disappointed" -- he acknowledges that "the symbolic structure of the West is based on biblical imagery. The symbols in Christianity are powerful despite popular disinterest in it as a religion."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Equipped with a nail, Mr. Scott, a part-time instructor at the Ontario College of Art in Toronto, scratched all 22 chapters from Revelation into every inch of a Trans Am primed with black latex paint. Now displayed in an airy rotunda at the National Gallery of Canada in Ottawa, the Trans Am has dice hanging from a rearview mirror and a license plate reading "Ex-Nihil 666."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>The dice refer to Albert Einstein's insistence of order in the universe and that "God does not play dice." The number 666 is the biblical number of the satanic beast someday to rule the world. "Ex nihil" is close to the Latin "ex nihilo," meaning "out of nothing."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>A video next to the car blasts rock music and shows rock musicians and riot scenes juxtaposed, with Mr. Scott laboriously carving verses, a Bible open before him.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>"The apocalypse is the perfect postmodern state," he says. "All history is present simultaneously." But apart from Georgia primitive artist Howard Finster, "people seem to be ignoring the date more than I thought they would. I can't think of anyone doing contemporary art because they are worrying about the world coming to an end."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Mr. Scott likens his work to Survival Research Laboratories, an avant-garde trio of nihilistic artists based in San Francisco. In the 1980s, SRL fused themes of heavy metal, stock car races, dead animals, warfare and male sexuality to create bombastic performances of what High Performance magazine termed "orgies of destruction." To the sound of explosions, shattering glass and gasoline motors, radio-controlled car-sized machines ripped into one other, spitting streams of liquid and spewing fumes.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>"Heavy-metal youth cultures are obsessed with death," Mr. Scott says. "The car symbolizes destructive masculine egos, environmental destruction, the follies of us all that lead to the end."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Not that all death imagery is bad. Gospel singer Pat Boone, shortly to release an album, "Pat Boone in a Metal Mood," claims heavy metal is filled with biblical images.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>In an interview in the November issue of Charisma magazine, he says the heavy metal group Megadeath reminds him of the ominous prophecies of Old Testament prophet Jeremiah and the Apostle John, writer of the Book of Revelation.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>"Many of the writers [of heavy metal] have come out of a religious background, who have seen the dark side of life, [and] now do have a tremendous sense of foreboding and of the ominous," he told the magazine.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Mr. Scott says, "The Book of Revelation, probably more than any other text, has informed Western consciousness. All heavy metal albums make reference to it, the beast, 666, all that stuff. A lot of heavy metal is anarchic, and there's a longing for an apocalypse where all order will be reversed."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>The recent hit movie "Independence Day" is a subtle hint of the End, Mr. Scott says, as "those ships, like the hand of God, sweep across the screen and then time ends." But it doesn't really. American know-how rescues the world once again -- a shame, the artist says. "People wanted the end to happen."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>The artist's confrontation with death gets personal, as Mr. Scott suffers from a degenerative bone disease that caused his body to shrink by 8 inches in one year.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>"I'm in constant pain," he says, "because I'm always breaking things. The vertebrae in your spine collapse and the cartilage compresses. All your organs are squished. Where it gets problematic is breathing. I'm sort of like a hunchback."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>"John's responding to the sense he will die and what he will do," says Joan Murray, director of the Robert McLaughlin Gallery in Oshawa, Ontario, which has displayed Mr. Scott's work. "This apocalyptic mood is current in the art field because of the problems the art community has with AIDS."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Nevertheless, Mr. Scott's melancholy art, which ranges from drawings of bunnies to skeletons, shows a "complete lack of self-pity," according to a recent review in the Toronto Globe and Mail. The passer-by may miss the artist's inner struggles, the reviewer wrote, but will surely see the artist's "inner work of reconciliation with death."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Mr. Scott's Trans Am was a hit nearly two years ago during a 1995 reception at the National Gallery hosted by President Clinton for Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>"Bill Clinton loved it, an American product in the National Gallery of Canada." the artist said. "I'm just glad it wasn't a Toyota."</TD></TR></TABLE> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN=1 ROWSPAN=1><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=9><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top> <TD ALIGN=left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1"><IMG SRC="../images/vertical.gif" WIDTH=9 HEIGHT=60 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="" border=0></TD></TR></TABLE> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN=1 ROWSPAN=1><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=180><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top><TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN=1 ROWSPAN=1><A HREF="mailto:wtadvt@wt.infi.net"><IMG SRC="../ads/house_ad.180.gif" WIDTH=180 HEIGHT=60 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="TWT House Ad 1" border=0></A></TD></TD></TABLE></TD></TD></TABLE><center><p><a href="#linkTOP">Go back to the top of this article.</A></center></TD></TR>
