VLINK="#6f6f6f" ALINK="#000000"></A>
<center><NOBR><IMG SRC="../images/twtbanner.gif" WIDTH=375 HEIGHT=42 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="The Washington Times" border=0>
<A HREF="../aboutNWE.html">
<IMG SRC="images/letters.gif" WIDTH=145 HEIGHT=42 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="Letters" border=0></A>
</NOBR>
<IMG SRC="../images/nwe.redrule.gif" WIDTH=520 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0><BR><NOBR><font size=-1>Published in Washington, D.C.<IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=0>&#009;<B>January 12, 1997 -- Edition</B>&#009;<IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=0>"America's Newspaper"<BR></font></NOBR><A HREF="buttons.3.gif.map"><MAP NAME="clientmap3"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="436,1,519,18" HREF="../watch/watch.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="351,1,428,16" HREF="#linkTOP"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="263,0,345,19" HREF="../stories/exclusive.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="177,1,257,18" HREF="../stories/culture.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="90,0,172,19" HREF="../stories/top.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="2,1,86,18" HREF="../index.html"></MAP><IMG SRC="images/buttons.3.gif" WIDTH=520 HEIGHT=19 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="Navigation Bar graphic, see text links below." border=0 USEMAP="#clientmap3" ISMAP></A><BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif"  ALIGN=top WIDTH=0 HEIGHT=8><BR><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=520><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN="3" ROWSPAN="5"><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=325><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1"><font size=7>Letters to the Editor<BR></font><FONT SIZE=6>Picket pocket</FONT><BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>In returning contributions to donors, the president reminds me of a fellow we knew in Odessa, Texas. When it was a boomtown, building sites "popped up" all over town. The fellow we knew, "Cowboy," said he visited the building sites at night and, spotting materials he liked, took a door here, a window there, a box of tile, cement blocks, wall panels, and siding until he had enough to build his own house.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>"Cowboy" had a nice little house with a picket fence around it when a man stopped by, saying, "Hey! Those look just like the pickets I bought. They went missing, and I believe you took them."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>"Cowboy" replied: "Those may be  your pickets, sir. I can't recall just where I got them. But if you think they're your pickets, you can have them. I guess you know your own pickets."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>So went his little house, brick by brick, door and window, panel and tile, until his little lot was vacant. "Cowboy" told his story without apology.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>That was several decades ago. But I must thank Bill Clinton for reminding me. "Cowboy" was a million laughs.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Mary D. May<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Benton, Arkansas<FONT SIZE=6><BR><BR>House cleaning?</FONT><BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Now that Newt Gingrich has fessed up to wrongdoing and unethical conduct, we have a good start -- a welcome crack in the stonewall.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>The next order of business should be a look into the unethical glass house of Mr. Gingrich's main accuser, David Bonior and the unethical nepotism of having his wife on his staff payroll.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>There was an obvious component of political gain in the Gingrich conduct, and that of Mr. Bonior is just as obviously a matter of personal financial gain.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>It should be noted that the current White House occupants have been motivated by both types of gain -- and in spades to boot. Mr. Bonior and his Democrat allies have been notably and predictably silent on this point.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>If we have begun a House-cleaning, though, let's do a good, thorough job of it.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Mr. Gingrich, at this juncture, is one point ahead by virtue of having confessed to his error. But if we are going to have a viable two-party system, we are going to have to see a goodly measure of integrity in both.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>We are hearing much chatter about "campaign finance reform." That is evasion. What we really need is people reform at all levels of government.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>G.W. DeArmond, Jr.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Estes Park, Colorado<FONT SIZE=6><BR><BR>No longer useful</FONT><BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>The president promised in July 1995 to eliminate or modify abusive affirmative action programs, defined by Mr. Clinton as any that have quotas, preferences for minorities or women, that cause reverse discrimination, have outlived their usefulness, or accomplished their purpose.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Many federal government programs, such as those at the Social Security Administration, violate all of the above. Yet neither the president nor the Justice Department has taken any action to eliminate or modify these abusive programs.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Perhaps it will take an act of Congress to correct these abuses.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Maurice Horn<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Administrative Law Judge<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Social Security Administration<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Office of Hearings and Appeals<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Jamestown, North Carolina<FONT SIZE=6><BR><BR>The right Iowa cornfield</FONT><BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>I appreciate letter-writer Bob Bearss' suggestion (Dec. 29 edition) to move the White House to an Iowa cornfield. His reasoning indicates his compassion and that, hopefully, Iowa ethics, honesty and morality would "rub off" on the current caretakers.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Iowans aren't accustomed to "city SLICKers," and on first reading of this suggestion, I wondered why we would want to take on this great task. After careful consideration, I can see that this is a win-win situation for everyone concerned and I would suggest that the move be made to my hometown.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Please consider the following:<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0><B>*</B> Costs are lower in Iowa, resulting in lower taxes.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0><B>*</B> My hometown has a hotel/motel tax. We would reduce our local tax burden by taxing the contributing patrons of the Clintons' motel business.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0><B>*</B> The state of Iowa is building a new prison in my hometown. This could come in real handy in the near future.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0><B>*</B> We have all of the major fast-food restaurants.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0><B>*</B> Having the White House in Iowa, Congress can go about its business with less meddling from the administration.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>So, as you can see, the entire country wins with the White House in Iowa.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Sam R. Hartman<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Fort Dodge, Iowa<FONT SIZE=6><BR><BR>Questions for William Cohen</FONT><BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Philip Gold deserves plaudits for "Homeland defense and the threat of nuclear terrorism" (Dec. 29 edition) in which he discusses America's total vulnerability to missile attack.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>It may interest readers to know that an organization known as Lawyers Opposed to Government Misconduct (LOGM), which consists of several hundred lawyers from around the country, has publicly called upon the Senate Armed Services Committee to ask the incoming defense secretary, Maine Sen. William Cohen, about these very issues during his upcoming confirmation hearing.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Specifically, LOGM has demanded that Mr. Cohen be asked pointedly for his views on the ongoing controversy between the executive branch and Congress over compliance with the Ballistic Missile Defense Act and the Defense Appropriations Act. For over a year, the administration has steadfastly refused to comply with the timetables and programmatic guidelines set forth in those statutes for development and deployment of two theater missile defense systems, the Army's THAAD and the Navy's Upper Tier system.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>This violation of federal law led this past year to congressional hearings on the matter and the filing of a federal lawsuit against President Clinton and Defense Secretary William Perry by 41 members of Congress to force the president to discharge his duty under Article II, Section 3 of the United States Constitution to "take care that the laws of the United States be faithfully executed."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>As lawyers, we are outraged by the Clinton administration's cavalier disregard for federal laws mandating the development and deployment of theater missile defenses. As citizens we believe that the United States Senate and the American people deserve to hear from Mr. Cohen whether he intends to comply with those laws or whether he intends to perpetuate his predecessor's legacy of stonewalling and delay on this important issue.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Only after a full airing of Mr. Cohen's views on this disturbing situation (and what he would do to rectify it) can the Senate and the American people make a final decision on Mr. Cohen's fitness for the office of secretary of defense.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Anthony J. Dennis, Esq.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Founder and President<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Lawyers Opposed<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>to Government Misconduct<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Hartford, Connecticut<FONT SIZE=6><BR><BR>Other watchdogs<BR>that wouldn't hunt</FONT><BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Regarding the editorial: "Why those media watchdogs wouldn't hunt," (Dec. 29, 1996) Mr. William Power was correct indeed that the "liberal" press has not been publishing all the damaging facts on Clinton. <BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>However, I believe he omitted to note that in reality this is the same sort of censorship that the press used in 1918-1988 Soviet Union and in 1933-1945 Germany, to protect Stalin and Lenin from public outrage.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>David F. Stone<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Kissimmee, Florida<FONT SIZE=6><BR><BR>Let's air it out</FONT><BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Joan Claybrook ("Claybrook objects to air-bag editorial (Dec. 15 edition) and her fellow statists simply cannot understand the concept of personal responsibility.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>The pertinent facts concerning the use of government's coercive powers in the automobile marketplace are: 1) Ms. Claybrook, more than any other individual, is responsible for government rules and regulations about airbags; 2) The number of supportive experts and public hearings and accuracy of "studies" are irrelevant. The fact remains that the best results come from individuals being responsible for themselves and leaving the market to  be controlled by their preferences; 3) Ms. Claybrook simply does not trust American consumers to make judgments about their purchases. The lives of some buyers' children have relevance in her logic system only to the extent that they were "studied" and that government actions comported to the recommendations of such studies.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Her claim that she "had no control over auto manufacturers that chose to develop the cheapest, rather than the best, air bags" is outrageous. Would Ms. Claybrook be more smug and self-satisfied if the public complaint involved the high cost of "the best air bags" instead of kids' lives?<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>The greatest danger to our republic (and the lives of all of our kids) is that the likes of Ms. Claybrook have been allowed to coercively impose their expertly informed judgments in the marketplace and that we mere consumers were denied the prerogative to "simply say no."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Albert B. Hall<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Friday Harbor, Washington<FONT SIZE=6><BR><BR>Grim reality?</FONT><BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>California's Proposition 209 received a majority of the vote. But, one person, a federal judge, elected by no one, accountable to nobody, tenured for life, thwarts the expressed will of the people. In a single biased judicial activist stroke, he declares that the constitutional provision of equal protection of the law is probably unconstitutional.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Proposition 209 very clearly declares all forms of discrimination illegal. This is the indisputable preamble of true democracy.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>No wonder there are already signs of rebellion in many parts of the country when the foundation of our nation is being undermined by judges and self-serving politicians.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>It is time to rein in the federal judiciary by making its members stand for election and be made accountable to the people. Judge Robert Bork's fear of an "out-of-control, runaway judicial system" now appears to be a grim reality.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Stephen J. Conway<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Banning, California</TD></TR></TABLE> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN=1 ROWSPAN=1><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=12><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top> <TD ALIGN=left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1"><IMG SRC="../images/vertical.gif" WIDTH=9 HEIGHT=280 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="" border=0></TD></TR></TABLE> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN=1 ROWSPAN=1><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=180><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top><TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN=1 ROWSPAN=1><A HREF="write.map"><MAP NAME="clientmap4"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="1,3,180,59" HREF="mailto:nated@infi.net"></MAP><IMG SRC="images/write.gif" WIDTH=180 HEIGHT=60 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="E-mail address: nated@infi.net" border=0 USEMAP="#clientmap4" ISMAP></A><BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif"  ALIGN=top WIDTH=0 HEIGHT=6><BR><font size=-1>We welcome your opinions on any topic. Every letter will be considered for publication, but we prefer those of fewer than 250 words. All letters may be edited for clarity and length. For verification purposes, be sure to include your address and a daytime telephone number for your letter to be considered for publication.</font><font size=-1><BR><BR></font><font size=-1>Snail mail your opinion to:<BR></font><font size=-1><B><center>Letters to the Editor<BR>National Weekly Edition<BR>3600 New York Ave., NE<BR>Washington D.C. 20002<BR>or<BR>FAX-line: 202-269-5934<BR>or<BR>Internet mail:<BR><A HREF="mailto:nated@infi.net">nated@infi.net</A><BR></center></B></font></TD></TD></TABLE></TD></TD></TABLE><center><p><a href="#linkTOP">Go back to the top of this article.</A></center></TD></TR>
