<title>December 30, 1996 Press Release</title>

<body>

<font size=-1>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
December 30, 1996<br>
CONTACT: Kristin Hansen -- (202) 393-2100. For Radio: Rebecca Biles.
</font>

<p>

<center><h2>MARIJUANA-FIGHTING TEAM LACKS<br>
PRESIDENTIAL LEADERSHIP</h2></center>

<p>

<b>WASHINGTON, D.C. --</b> In response to California and Arizona
drug legalization propositions, a Clinton Administration team
presented Monday its campaign against further drug legalization.
&quot;The only problem was that the team was missing its quarterback.
President Clinton needs to personally tackle this national crisis,&quot;
Family Research Council Senior Policy Analyst Lt. Col. Robert
Maginnis said.

<p>

The success of the referenda, which were funded in part by billionaire
legalization entrepreneur George Soros, gives new life to the
national movement towards drug legalization.

<p>

Even before the ballot initiatives passed, marijuana use had been
on the rise for five years.  The National Institute on Drug Abuse's
recent Monitoring the Future Survey shows one in five 10th graders
used marijuana within the past month.

<p>

&quot;Use is up because the pop culture is pro-marijuana,&quot;
Maginnis said, &quot;and using marijuana is lightly portrayed
or treated as inconsequential behavior.  The recent propositions
will further weaken adolescent risk perception.

<p>

&quot;The consequences of not treating this as a crisis are severe.
Medical costs will increase as adolescent use continues to skyrocket,
the number of marijuana-related automobile accidents will rise,
law enforcement problems will abound, and both business and foreign
policy concerns will be complicated.&quot;

<p>

Maginnis said that pot legalization is more widespread than the
California and Arizona propositions, yet the Administration's
plan does not address other pro-marijuana laws.  At one time,
34 states had passed &quot;some endorsement of a medical use of
marijuana.&quot;  Some of these laws are still on the books and
have been re-energized by the recent referenda successes.  Virginia,
for example, has a criminal law that permits crude marijuana use
solely based on the recommendation of a physician from any state.

<p>

&quot;This is a national problem that requires the president's
personal attention,&quot; Maginnis said.  &quot;President Clinton
has already said: 'We cannot walk away from the fight against
drugs...we have to walk right into it.'  Mr. President, you must
now 'walk right into' this battle.  Don't send your subordinates
out to do what only you can do.  Pro-pot forces will stop at nothing
to advance their cause -- they already have a big foot in the
door.  Don't turn your back on our children.&quot;

<p>

